{"title_page": "Douglas Nicholls", "text_new": "{{short description|Governor of South Australia (1976-77)}}\n{{for|the British trade union leader|Doug Nicholls (trade unionist)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder  \n| image               = Douglas nicholls.jpg\n| honorific-prefix    = [[Pastor]]\n|name                 = Sir Douglas Nicholls  \n| honorific-suffix    = {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}\n| order               = 28th \n| office              = Governor of South Australia\n| term_start          = 1 December 1976\n| term_end            = 30 April 1977\n| lieutenant          = \n| premier             = \n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor         = [[Mark Oliphant|Sir Mark Oliphant]]\n| successor           = [[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1906|12|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cummeragunja Reserve]], [[New South Wales]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1988|6|4|1906|12|9|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Mooroopna, Victoria]]\n| nationality         = Australian \n| profession          = Pastor\n| spouse = [[Gladys Nicholls]]\n}}\n'''Sir Douglas Ralph Nicholls''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}  (9 December 1906 \u2013 4 June 1988) was a prominent [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal Australian]] from the [[Yorta Yorta people]]. He was a professional athlete, [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Churches of Christ]] pastor and [[church planter]], ceremonial officer and a pioneering campaigner for [[wiktionary:reconciliation|reconciliation]].\n\nNicholls was the first Aboriginal Australian to be knighted when he was appointed [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1972 (he was subsequently appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] in 1977).<ref>https://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/SiteCollectionDocuments/nicholls-biographies.pdf</ref><ref name=\"pressreader.com\">https://www.pressreader.com/australia/shepparton-news/20160527/282187945262970</ref> He was also the first \u2014 and to date the only<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-05-25/pastor-doug-nicholls-afl-indigenous-round/7437474|title=Pioneering Sir Doug Nicholls remembered in AFL tribute|last=Sexton|first=Mike|date=2016-05-25|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \u2014 Indigenous Australian to be appointed to [[vice-regal]] office, serving as [[Governor of South Australia]] from 1 December 1976 until his resignation on 30 April 1977 due to poor health.\n\n==Early life==\nNicholls was born on 9 December 1906 on the [[Cummeragunja Reserve]] in New South Wales.<ref>Clark, Mavis Thorpe (1956). Pastor Doug: The Story of Sir Douglas Nicholls Aboriginal Leader (Rev. ed.). Melbourne: Lansdowne Press. SBN 8018-0017-8.</ref><ref name=adb-bio>Richard Broome, 'Nicholls, Sir Douglas Ralph (Doug) (1906\u20131988)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nicholls-sir-douglas-ralph-doug-14920/text26109, published first in hardcopy 2012, accessed online 19 December 2015.</ref> He was the youngest of five children born to Herbert Nicholls and Florence Atkinson.<ref name=abc-blood>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s3014566.htm |title=Bloodlines: The Nicholls Family |last=Corowa |first=Miriam |date=19 September 2010 |work=Message Stick |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=3 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112123902/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s3014566.htm |archive-date=12 January 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His paternal grandfather was Aaron Atkinson, who was the brother of [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]].\n\nSchooling at Nicholls's mission was provided to Grade 3 standard and strict religious principles were emphasised. When he was eight, he saw his 16-year-old sister Hilda forcibly taken from his family by the police and taken to the [[Cootamundra Domestic Training Home for Aboriginal Girls]] where she was trained to become a domestic servant.\n\nAt 13 Nicholls worked with his uncle as a tar boy and general hand on [[sheep station]]s, and he lived with the shearers. He worked hard and had a cheerful disposition. This annoyed one of the shearers so much that he challenged Nicholls to a fight, with the loser to hand over one week's pay (30 [[Australian pound|shillings]] \u2013 [[Australian dollar|$]]3). After six rounds the shearer who challenged him conceded defeat.\n\n==Sporting career==\n[[File:Northcote 1929.jpg|left|thumb|[[Northcote Football Club]]'s 1929 premiership side. Doug Nicholls is second from right, front row.]]\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Football career\n| image =\n| caption =\n| height = 157&nbsp;cm\n| weight = 65&nbsp;kg\n| originalteam = [[Tongala Football Club|Tongala]]\n| years1 = 1927\u20131931\n| club1 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| games_goals1 = \n| years2 = 1932\u20131937\n| club2 = [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]]\n| games_goals2 = 54 (2)\n| years3 = 1937\u20131938\n| club3 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| games_goals3 = \n| games_goalstotal =\n| sooyears1 = 1935\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = {{0}}4 {{0|00}}(0)\n| coachyears1 = 1947\n| coachclub1 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 20 (4\u201316\u20130)\n| careerhighlights =\n* VFA premiership player: [[1929 VFA season#1929 VFA premiership|1929]]\n}}\n\nNicholls played [[Australian rules football]]. After playing in the Goulburn Valley for [[Tongala Football Club|Tongala]], Nicholls tried out for [[Australian Football League|VFL]] clubs {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Car}} before the 1927 season;<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Association's best centre man|page=9|date=27 August 1930}}</ref> Nicholls played some seconds matches for Carlton but did not play a senior game.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Nicholls under ban|page=9|date=10 June 1931}}</ref> He subsequently joined the [[Northcote Football Club]] in the [[Victorian Football Association|VFA]], and became a regular in the Northcote team by 1929. He made his name as an energetic and speedy wingman, capable of spectacular feats, and came to be regarded as the best wingman in the VFA at the time. At 5'2\", he was one of the shortest players in the game.<ref name=\"victor\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Black ball of muscle|date=18 May 1929|page=6|author=\"Victor\"}}</ref> He was a member of Northcote's 1929 premiership team, and finished third in the [[Recorder Cup]] voting in 1931, his final season with Northcote.<ref name=\"SF1\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Argus|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Association \u2013 first semi-final|date=7 September 1931|page=12|author=Onlooker}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Nicholls joined the VFL's [[Fitzroy Football Club]] and in 1935, he was the first Aboriginal player to be selected to play for the [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victorian interstate team]], ultimately playing four interstate games. He played a total of six seasons for Fitzroy, before returning to Northcote in 1938.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|date=4 May 1938|page=3|title=\"Duggie\" cheers Northcote}}</ref> Knee injuries forced him to retire in 1939. He returned to Northcote as non-playing coach in 1947.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Rev. Doug. Nicholls to coach Northcote|page=4|date=25 January 1947}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career, particularly in the early years, Nicholls was subjected to onfield taunts or ostracised by his team-mates due to his colour. Nevertheless, he became a popular player among spectators; and, upon joining Fitzroy, when he was initially sitting by himself in the change rooms (due to this ostracism), he was befriended by [[Haydn Bunton, Sr.]] who ensured he was made welcome within the team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110679183 |title=A legend in his time. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |location=ACT |date=25 September 1971 |accessdate=24 August 2015 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australianrules.com.au/2003stories/buntonstory.html |title=Haydn Bunton \u2013 legend and myth |last=Mansell |first=Ken |date=17 June 2003 |accessdate=9 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726052821/http://australianrules.com.au/2003stories/buntonstory.html |archivedate=26 July 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLike his close relative [[Lynch Cooper]], Nicholls was also a very capable sprinter. He competed in gift races around Victoria during the athletics seasons, and in 1928 he won both the Nyah and Warracknabeal Gifts.<ref name=\"victor\" /> Following this, the race organisers paid him an appearance fee, board and expenses to enter races. He was the inaugural chairman of the National Aboriginal Sports Foundation.\n\nPlaying football provided employment during the winter. To earn a living during the rest of the year, he [[boxing|boxed]] with [[Jimmy Sharman]]'s Boxing Troupe, a travelling sideshow in which Sharman offered his fighters for challenge against all comers.\n\nDuring World War II, Nicholls was an adept [[boomerang]] thrower, teaching that skill to some members of the United States military. There is a photograph depicting this in the Australian War Memorial archives.<ref>[https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/141672/ Australian War Memorial website. |1944-09-04 Doug Nicholls, an Australian Aborigine and ex-Fitzroy footballer, demonstrating the art of throwing a boomerang to Lieutenant Colonel Forrest M.Carhartt of the United States Army.]</ref> He also organised and captained Aboriginal teams in football matches used for patriotic fundraisers during the war, many of which were played against Northcote.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Argus|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Northcote to play against Aborigines|page=18|date=14 June 1946}}</ref>\n\n==The long road to the 1967 Referendum==\n[[File:President Patten (right) reads resolution (12097104296).jpg|thumb|Tom Foster, Jack Kinchela (obscured), Doug Nicholls, [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], and [[Jack Patten]] reading the resolution of the Aborigines Progressive Association at the All Australian Aboriginal Conference and Day of Mourning at Australian Hall, Sydney on 26 January 1938. ]]\n[[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], an uncle to Nicholls, mentored him in leadership, eventually placing him as the secretary of the [[Australian Aborigines' League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ia.anu.edu.au/biography/nicholls-sir-douglas-ralph-doug-14920|title=Biography - Sir Douglas Ralph (Doug) Nicholls - Indigenous Australia|website=ia.anu.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It was a founding principle of the League that Aboriginal Affairs was made a Federal matter, which would require a change in the [[Constitution of Australia]], which could only be effected by a referendum. As early as February 1935 Cooper, Nicholls and others were lobbying Members of Parliament, such as [[Thomas Paterson]], the Commonwealth minister for the interior on this issue. It gained national attention when Nicholls, leveraging his profile as a nationally famous athlete, participated in the [[Day of Mourning (Australia)|Day of Mourning]] protest for Aborigines held in Sydney on 26 January 1938, where Indigenous leaders from across the country made the demand to change the Constitution. The proposed resolution was: <blockquote>WE, representing THE ABORIGINES OF AUSTRALIA, assembled in conference at the Australian Hall, Sydney, on the 26th day of January, 1938, this being the 150th Anniversary of the Whiteman's seizure of our country, HEREBY MAKE PROTEST against the callous treatment of our people by the whitemen during the past 150 years, AND WE APPEAL to the Australian nation of today to make new laws for the education and care of Aborigines, we ask for a new policy which will raise our people TO FULL CITIZEN STATUS and EQUALITY WITHIN THE COMMUNITY.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/day-mourning-26th-january-1938|title=Day of Mourning - 26th January 1938|date=2018-01-08|website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> </blockquote>Doug Nicholls rose to support the resolution on behalf of the Victorian Aborigines League that day, saying:  <blockquote>On behalf of Victorian Aborigines I want to say that we support this resolution in every way. The public does not realise what our people have suffered for 150 years. Aboriginal girls have been sent to Aboriginal Reserves and have not been given any opportunity to improve themselves. Their treatment has been disgusting. The white people have done nothing for us whatever. Put on Reserves, with no proper education, how can Aborigines take their place as equals with whites? Now is our chance to have things altered. We must fight our very hardest in this cause. After 150 years our people are still bossed and influenced by white people. I know that we could proudly hold our own with others if given the chance. Do not let us forget, also, those of our own people who are still in a primitive state. It is for them that we should try to do something. We should all work in co-operation for the progress of Aborigines throughout the Commonwealth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.teachingheritage.nsw.edu.au/section07/wc2_1938speeches.php|title=- Board of Studies NSW|last=NSW|first=Board of Studies|last2=NSW|first2=Board of Studies|website=www.teachingheritage.nsw.edu.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Logo of the Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders.png|thumb|Nicholls was one of the founders of the Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]]\nThe movement took 30 years to coalesce and achieve anything like its stated goal, but it soon made its focus the Constitution of Australia which, in its original form, prevented the Commonwealth from making any law that would benefit the Aboriginal people. In 1949, a letter written by Nicholls prompted the Labor MP, [[Kim Beazley Sr.]] to write to Prime Minister [[Ben Chifley]] asking him to explore how the Constitution could be amended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au/learningobjects/Content/R10908/object/r11027.html|title=Doug Nicholls|website=tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In 1957, [[Jessie Street]] approached Nicholls about bringing in the Victorian Aboriginal Advancement League to form a federal council to campaign for Aboriginal affairs to become a federal matter \u2014 this would became the [[Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]]. Its early work involved drafting and collecting petitions, from suburbs and town centres from across the country. By 1962 they had achieved 100,000 signatures<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au/learningobjects/Content/R10908/object/r7882.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=NSW Department of Education and Training|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> with the stated goal of 250,000 signatures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nma.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/692620/goal-of-250000-signatures.pdf|title=250,000 Signatures to be sought on Native-Rights Petition|last=|first=|date=October 2, 1962|website=National Museum of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The movement supporting a change to the constitution, which removed the block on the Federal Government making a laws regarding Aboriginal people, soon became known as the \"yes\" campaign.  \n[[File:Harold Holt and FCAATSI.jpg|thumb|Pastor Doug Nicholls in a meeting Prime Minister Harold Holt, three months before the 1967 referendum. With him are several members of (FCAATSI) \u2013 from left to right: Gordon Bryant, Faith Bandler, Harold Holt, Doug Nicholls, Burnum Burnum, Winnie Branson, and Bill Wentworth.]]\nFCAATSI would later became the central lobby group who were able to interface with the Federal Government. During this time Pastor Doug was known to have met and negotiated with Prime Ministers [[Robert Menzies]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Harold Holt]]. However, creating the political momentum involved substantial grass roots action. Nicholls' daughter, Pam recalls her father winning support from white Australians at football games: <blockquote>\u201cWith his friend Alick Jackomos, they used to have a card table and go and sit outside the football giving out papers, giving speeches, beckoning people to come sign the petitions for the \u2018yes\u2019 vote.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Riordan|first=Primrose|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/1967-indigenous-referendum-citizenship-one-footy-fan-at-a-time/news-story/e4edbc62a7e534a1f05ed79ae0da491e|title=1967 indigenous referendum: citizenship, one footy fan at a time|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>Nicholls interacted with the media frequently. Drawing on his abilities as a preacher, he was able to deliver pithy, persuasive messages which were effective in winning over the Australian public. One common line of argument he made was for the \"Yes\" vote was:<blockquote>\u201cI think it\u2019s a matter of democratic right. And we will form a part of the British commonwealth of nations and there should be no legislation setup to discriminate us.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aikman|first=Amos|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/how-the-1967-referendum-unfolded/news-story/c20726a61f4c0f769f80c48af67ccc4e|title=How the 1967 referendum unfolded|date=May 27, 2017|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>The [[1967 Australian referendum]] was an emphatic success for Nicholls and the FCAATSI leadership, with an average of 90% of Australians<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/right-wrongs-write-yes-what-was-the-1967-referendum-all-about-76512|title=\u2018Right wrongs, write Yes\u2019: what was the 1967 referendum all about?|last=McGregor|first=Russell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> supporting the change they had asked for. Following the successful outcome of the referendum, Pastor Doug argued that much more than a legal change had been made, rather, it was:<blockquote>\u2026 evidence that Australians recognise Aborigines are part of the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/right-wrongs-write-yes-what-was-the-1967-referendum-all-about-76512|title=\u2018Right wrongs, write Yes\u2019: what was the 1967 referendum all about?|last=McGregor|first=Russell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Community work and Christian ministry==\nNicholls was a minister and [[social work]]er with [[Australian Aborigine|Aboriginal people]]. Following his mother's death he took a renewed interest in Christianity and was baptised at Northcote [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Church of Christ]] (now Northern Community Church of Christ) in 1935. He officiated at church and hymn services as a [[lay preacher]] at the Gore Street Mission Centre in [[Fitzroy, Victoria|Fitzroy]].\n\nIn 1941 Nicholls received his call-up notice and he joined the [[2/29th Battalion (Australia)|29th Battalion]] but, in 1942, at the request of the Fitzroy police, he was released from his unit to work as a [[social worker]] in the Fitzroy Aboriginal community. He cared for those trapped in [[alcohol abuse]], gambling, and other social problems, and those who were in trouble with the police. Indigenous people gathered to him and eventually the group was so large that he became the pastor of the first Aboriginal [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Church of Christ]] in Australia. In recognition of the ministry he was already expressing, he was ordained as a minister.\n\nIn a letter to the editor, in 1953, it was noted that Opposition Leader, [[H. V. Evatt]], had asked the Prime Minister [[Robert Menzies]], on 26 February, in Federal Parliament, 'for an invitation to be extended to Capt. Reg Saunders or some other outstanding representative of the aborigines' to be included in the official [[Australia]]n contingent to the [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|coronation]] of [[Elizabeth II]]. The author suggested Nicholls, as an ordained minister, and for his community work in the areas of [[Fitzroy, Victoria|Fitzroy]] and [[Mooroopna, Victoria|Mooroopna]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64434531 |title=ABORIGINE FOR CORONATION?. |newspaper=[[Portland Guardian|Portland Guardian (Vic. : 1876 - 1953)]] |location=Vic. |date=16 April 1953 |accessdate=27 September 2013 |page=4 Edition: MIDDAY |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957 Nicholls became a field officer for the [[Aborigines Advancement League]]. He edited their magazine, ''Smoke Signals'', and helped draw Aboriginal issues to the attention of Government officials and the general public. He pleaded for dignity for Aboriginal people as human beings. Support for the AAL grew rapidly.\n\nNicholls helped set up hostels for Aboriginal children, holiday homes for Aboriginal people at [[Queenscliff, Victoria|Queenscliff]] and was a founding member and Victorian Secretary of the [[Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]] (FCAATSI). In response to protests in the 1950s and 60s for an independent, Aboriginal-run farming cooperative at [[Lake Tyers Mission]] he campaigned on their behalf, but when the board moved to close Lake Tyers, Nichols resigned his position in protest.<ref name=\"ABC\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-21/lake-tyers-history-piece/5170896 A brief history of the Lake Tyers Aboriginal community, By Jeff Waters, ABC Radio, 21 Dec 2013]</ref>\n\nNicholls was an active [[Freemasonry|Freemason]].<ref name=\"bio\">[http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Indigenous/BIOGRAPHIES_FOR_NICHOLLS.DOC Biographies of Doug and Gladys Nicholls] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730211511/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Indigenous/BIOGRAPHIES_FOR_NICHOLLS.DOC |date=30 July 2008 }}, Council of Melbourne (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref>\n\n==Governor of South Australia==\n[[File:Douglas Nicholls 1977.jpg|thumb|Pastor Sir Douglas Nicholls is sworn in as Governor of South Australia, in front of Premier Don Dunstan and other dignitaries 1977]]\nNicholls was appointed [[Governor of South Australia]] on 1 December 1976, on the nomination of Premier [[Don Dunstan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131798665|title=Historic, says Sir Douglas|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=2 December 1976}}</ref> He was the first non-white person to serve as the governor of an Australian state, and is the only Aboriginal person to have held viceregal office. Because of his race, his nomination proved controversial and attracted more attention than most viceregal appointments. A poll by ABC's ''[[This Day Tonight]]'' found that 70 percent of respondents opposed Nicholls becoming governor. ''[[The Canberra Times]]'' expressed concern that members of his family might set up camp on the grounds of [[Government House, Adelaide|Government House]]. However, Adelaide's main daily newspaper ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' was more positive, welcoming the news \"without reservation\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819165|title=Next Governor may test community's racial tolerance|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=25 May 1976}}</ref> News of the appointment was leaked in May 1976, after which he agreed to appear on ''[[A Current Affair (Australian TV program)|A Current Affair]]''. Nicholls took exception to a question directed at his wife, calling the interviewer a racist and requiring him to leave his house.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819394|title=Sir Douglas angered|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=26 May 1976}}</ref> [[GTV (Australia)|GTV-9]] aired the footage without his permission, and subsequently apologised for doing so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819719|title=Apology|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=27 May 1976}}</ref>\n\nNicholls' predecessor as governor, nuclear physicist [[Mark Oliphant]], confidentially wrote to the state government expressing concerns about the appointment. He said there were \"grave dangers\" involved, as \"there is something inherent in the personality of the Aborigine which makes it difficult for him to adapt fully to the ways of the white man\".<ref name=\"Black\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Age]] |date=20 August 1981 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19810820&id=6zJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h5QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3739,1176081 |title=Oliphant did not want Black |accessdate=7 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511050518/https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19810820&id=6zJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h5QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3739,1176081 |archive-date=11 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 1977, Nicholls suffered a stroke and was admitted to the cardiac ward at [[Royal Adelaide Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110837268|title=Sir Douglas Nicholls in hospital|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=26 January 1977}}</ref> He had a history of high blood pressure and had suffered a mild heart attack some years earlier.<ref name=resign>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110733486|title=Nicholls to resign as SA Governor|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=19 April 1977}}</ref> He was not discharged until three weeks later,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110841256|title=Discharged|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=16 February 1977}}</ref> with Lieutenant-Governor [[Walter Crocker]] serving as [[Administrator (Australia)|Administrator of the Government]] in his place.<ref name=resign/> Nicholls attended only one further official engagement after his stroke, hosting Queen [[Elizabeth II]] at Government House on 20 March.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110729441 The Canberra Times], 21 March 1977.</ref> She subsequently awarded him a second knighthood, [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO).<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110729930 The Canberra Times], 24 March 1977</ref> Nicholls' retirement due to ill health was announced on 22 April, with effect from 30 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110734432|title=Governor officially resigns|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=23 April 1977}}</ref> He held office for only 150 days, making him the shortest-serving governor in South Australian history and the only governor to serve for less than a year.\n\n==Family==\nIn December 1942 Nicholls married [[Gladys Nicholls]], the widow of his brother Howard Nicholls (1905\u20131942); Howard (who had married Gladys in 1927) had died in April 1942 as a result of injuries sustained in a car accident. Gladys already had three children. Douglas Nicholls and Gladys were married for 39 years and raised their combined six children; two sons, Bevan and Ralph, and four daughters, Beryl, Nora, Lilian and Pamela.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Lady Gladys Nicholls died in 1981.\n\nNicholls' great grandson [[Nathan Lovett-Murray]] also played [[Australian Rules Football]], playing 145 games for [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]].<ref>http://australianfootball.com/players/player/nathan%2Blovett-murray/14592</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Pastor Sir Douglas and Lady Gladys Nicholls Memorial.jpg|thumb|300px|Statue in Parliament Gardens, [[East Melbourne, Victoria]]]]\n* 1957 \u2013 appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE).\n* 1962 \u2013 chosen by the Father's Day Council of Australia as Victoria's Father of the Year for \"outstanding leadership in youth and welfare work and for the inspired example he set the community in his unfailing efforts to further the cause of the Australian Aborigine\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fathersdaycouncil.org.au/past-winners/|title=Past winners|date=2012-05-08|work=Father's Day Council of Victoria Inc.|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* 1968 \u2013 promoted to Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE).\n* 1970 \u2013 among Victorians invited guests to greet [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] on her visit to Australia.\n* 1972 \u2013 first Aboriginal to be knighted when he was appointed [[Knight Bachelor]];<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1083655&search_type=advanced&showInd=true Knight Bachelor] itsanhonour.gov.au</ref> he and his wife Gladys travelled to London to receive that honour.<ref name=\"pressreader.com\"/>\n* 1973 \u2013 appointed [[Moomba|King of Moomba]].<ref>Craig Bellamy, Gordon Chisholm, Hilary Eriksen (17 February 2006) ''Moomba: A festival for the people.'': {{cite web|url=http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Moomba/History%20of%20Moomba.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028203816/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Moomba/History%20of%20Moomba.pdf |archivedate=28 October 2009}} PDF pp 17\u201322 also p 8 for photo</ref>\n* 1976 \u2013 appointed the 28th Governor of South Australia, the first Aboriginal person appointed to vice-regal office.\n* 1977 \u2013 appointed a Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (KCVO)<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1082642&search_type=advanced&showInd=true KCVO] itsanhonour.gov.au</ref>\n* 1991 \u2013 the [[Canberra]] suburb of [[Nicholls, Australian Capital Territory|Nicholls]] was named after him\n* 2001 \u2013 a new chapel in Preston of the Northern Community Church of Christ, the church in which he was baptized, is named after him.\n* 2006 \u2013 to commemorate the centenary of his birth, a statue of Nicholls, one-and-a-half times life size, was approved for the Parliament Gardens, beside the Parliament of Victoria;<ref>[http://one.melbourne.vic.gov.au/opm/bc/CTEE/meetings/EC_34_200605160700.pdf Memorial for Pastor Sir Doug and Lady Nicholls]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, submission by Assets and Services Division, Council of Melbourne, 16 May 2006 (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref> it was officially opened in December 2007<ref>[http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/info.cfm?top=251&pg=2045 City of Melbourne \u2013 Walks and tours \u2013 Sir Douglas and Lady Gladys Nicholls Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013050015/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/info.cfm?top=251&pg=2045 |date=13 October 2007 }}, City of Melbourne (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref> and was the first statue of an Aboriginal erected in Victoria.\n*2011 \u2013 inducted to Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vic.gov.au/aboriginalvictoria/community-engagement/leadership-programs/aboriginal-honour-roll/2011-victorian-aboriginal-honour-roll.html|title=2011 Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll|website=www.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> \n* 2016 \u2013 The [[Australian Football League|AFL]] named their \"[[Indigenous round]]\" after him, and continue to do so.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/28/afl-to-honour-sir-doug-nicholls-in-2016-indigenous-round AFL to honour Sir Doug Nicholls in 2016 Indigenous round], [[The Guardian]], 28 October 2015</ref><ref name=Guard>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/28/afl-to-honour-sir-doug-nicholls-in-2016-indigenous-round|title=AFL to honour Sir Doug Nicholls in 2016 Indigenous round|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> Each year, each player in all 18 clubs wears a specially-commissioned artwork by an Indigenous artist on their guernsey.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/afl-indigenous-guernseys-revealed-and-the-stories-behind-them-20190521-p51pme.html|newspaper=The Age|title=AFL Indigenous guernseys revealed, and the stories behind them|first=Charlotte|last=Grieve|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 The federal electoral division of Murray is renamed Nicholls in honour of Sir Doug and Lady Nicholls.<ref>https://www.sheppnews.com.au/@news/2018/06/29/135789/xx-3</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 a [[Google Doodle]] was created to celebrate his 112th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/sir-douglas-nicholls-112th-birthday |title=Sir Douglas Nicholls' 112th Birthday |website=www.google.com |language=en |access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Doug Nicholls Grave IMG 0977.jpg|thumb|Grave of Douglas and Gladys Nicholls at Cummeragunja Cemetery]] [[File:Doug Nicholas Grave IMG 0978.jpg|thumb|Headstone of grave of Doug Nicholls and his wife]]\n\n==Death==\nNicholls died on 4 June 1988 at Mooroopna. A [[state funeral]] was held for him and he was buried in the cemetery at Cummeragunja.<ref name=adb-bio/>\n\n==Sources==\n* Clark, M. (1972) ''Pastor Doug'', Lansdowne Press, Melbourne. {{ISBN|0-7018-0017-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120717070313/http://www.kooriweb.org/foley/heroes/nicholls.html Biography of Sir Douglas Nicholls (Pastor)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050624192309/http://www.decc.org.au/fourteen.htm Biography of Douglas Nicholls at Darebin Ethnic Communities Council site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050417170027/http://abc.net.au/missionvoices/cummeragunja/default.htm ABC Mission Voices \u2013 Cummeragunja. Koorie Heritage Trust]\n* [http://www.michaelwinkler.com.au/PDF/The%20great%20Pastor%20Sir%20Doug%20Nicholls.pdf The Great Australian: Pastor Sir Doug Nicholls]\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=D/Doug_Nicholls.html}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Mark Oliphant|Sir Mark Oliphant]] |\n  after=[[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] |\n  title=[[Governor of South Australia]] |\n  years=1976\u20131977\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of South Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicholls, Douglas}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Christian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian players of Australian rules football]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian boxers]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Fitzroy Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Northcote Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Northcote Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Tongala Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Australian Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Australian members of the Churches of Christ]]\n[[Category:Australian male boxers]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Bachelor]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Governor of South Australia (1976-77)}}\n{{for|the British trade union leader|Doug Nicholls (trade unionist)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder  \n| image               = Douglas nicholls.jpg\n| honorific-prefix    = [[Pastor]]\n|name                 = Sir Douglas Nicholls  \n| honorific-suffix    = {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}\n| order               = 28th \n| office              = Governor of South Australia\n| term_start          = 1 December 1976\n| term_end            = 30 April 1977\n| lieutenant          = \n| premier             = \n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor         = [[Mark Oliphant|Sir Mark Oliphant]]\n| successor           = [[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1906|12|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cummeragunja Reserve]], [[New South Wales]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1988|6|4|1906|12|9|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Mooroopna, Victoria]]\n| nationality         = Australian \n| profession          = Pastor\n| spouse = [[Gladys Nicholls]]\n}}\n'''Sir Douglas Ralph Nicholls''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}  (9 December 1906 \u2013 4 June 1988) was a prominent [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal Australian]] from the [[Yorta Yorta people]]. He was a professional athlete, [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Churches of Christ]] pastor and [[church planter]], ceremonial officer and a pioneering campaigner for [[wiktionary:reconciliation|reconciliation]].\n\nNicholls was the first Aboriginal Australian to be knighted when he was appointed [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1972 (he was subsequently appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] in 1977).<ref>https://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/SiteCollectionDocuments/nicholls-biographies.pdf</ref><ref name=\"pressreader.com\">https://www.pressreader.com/australia/shepparton-news/20160527/282187945262970</ref> He was also the first \u2014 and to date the only<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-05-25/pastor-doug-nicholls-afl-indigenous-round/7437474|title=Pioneering Sir Doug Nicholls remembered in AFL tribute|last=Sexton|first=Mike|date=2016-05-25|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \u2014 Indigenous Australian to be appointed to [[vice-regal]] office, serving as [[Governor of South Australia]] from 1 December 1976 until his resignation on 30 April 1977 due to poor health.\n\n==Early life==\nNicholls was born on 9 December 1906 on the [[Cummeragunja Reserve]] in New South Wales.<ref>Clark, Mavis Thorpe (1956). Pastor Doug: The Story of Sir Douglas Nicholls Aboriginal Leader (Rev. ed.). Melbourne: Lansdowne Press. SBN 8018-0017-8.</ref><ref name=adb-bio>Richard Broome, 'Nicholls, Sir Douglas Ralph (Doug) (1906\u20131988)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nicholls-sir-douglas-ralph-doug-14920/text26109, published first in hardcopy 2012, accessed online 19 December 2015.</ref> He was the youngest of five children born to Herbert Nicholls and Florence Atkinson.<ref name=abc-blood>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s3014566.htm |title=Bloodlines: The Nicholls Family |last=Corowa |first=Miriam |date=19 September 2010 |work=Message Stick |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=3 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112123902/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s3014566.htm |archive-date=12 January 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His paternal grandfather was Aaron Atkinson, who was the brother of [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]].\n\nSchooling at Nicholls's mission was provided to Grade 3 standard and strict religious principles were emphasised. When he was eight, he saw his 16-year-old sister Hilda forcibly taken from his family by the police and taken to the [[Cootamundra Domestic Training Home for Aboriginal Girls]] where she was trained to become a domestic servant.\n\nAt 13 Nicholls worked with his uncle as a tar boy and general hand on [[sheep station]]s, and he lived with the shearers. He worked hard and had a cheerful disposition. This annoyed one of the shearers so much that he challenged Nicholls to a fight, with the loser to hand over one week's pay (30 [[Australian pound|shillings]] \u2013 [[Australian dollar|$]]3). After six rounds the shearer who challenged him conceded defeat.\n\n==Sporting career==\n[[File:Northcote 1929.jpg|left|thumb|[[Northcote Football Club]]'s 1929 premiership side. Doug Nicholls is second from right, front row.]]\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Football career\n| image =\n| caption =\n| height = 157&nbsp;cm\n| weight = 65&nbsp;kg\n| originalteam = [[Tongala Football Club|Tongala]]\n| years1 = 1927\u20131931\n| club1 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| games_goals1 = \n| years2 = 1932\u20131937\n| club2 = [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]]\n| games_goals2 = 54 (2)\n| years3 = 1937\u20131938\n| club3 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| games_goals3 = \n| games_goalstotal =\n| sooyears1 = 1935\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = {{0}}4 {{0|00}}(0)\n| coachyears1 = 1947\n| coachclub1 = [[Northcote Football Club|Northcote]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 20 (4\u201316\u20130)\n| careerhighlights =\n* VFA premiership player: [[1929 VFA season#1929 VFA premiership|1929]]\n}}\n\nNicholls played [[Australian rules football]]. After playing in the Goulburn Valley for [[Tongala Football Club|Tongala]], Nicholls tried out for [[Australian Football League|VFL]] clubs {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Car}} before the 1927 season;<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Association's best centre man|page=9|date=27 August 1930}}</ref> Nicholls played some seconds matches for Carlton but did not play a senior game.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Nicholls under ban|page=9|date=10 June 1931}}</ref> He subsequently joined the [[Northcote Football Club]] in the [[Victorian Football Association|VFA]], and became a regular in the Northcote team by 1929. He made his name as an energetic and speedy wingman, capable of spectacular feats, and came to be regarded as the best wingman in the VFA at the time. At 5'2\", he was one of the shortest players in the game.<ref name=\"victor\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Black ball of muscle|date=18 May 1929|page=6|author=\"Victor\"}}</ref> He was a member of Northcote's 1929 premiership team, and finished third in the [[Recorder Cup]] voting in 1931, his final season with Northcote.<ref name=\"SF1\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Argus|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Association \u2013 first semi-final|date=7 September 1931|page=12|author=Onlooker}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Nicholls joined the VFL's [[Fitzroy Football Club]] and in 1935, he was the first Aboriginal player to be selected to play for the [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victorian interstate team]], ultimately playing four interstate games. He played a total of six seasons for Fitzroy, before returning to Northcote in 1938.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|date=4 May 1938|page=3|title=\"Duggie\" cheers Northcote}}</ref> Knee injuries forced him to retire in 1939. He returned to Northcote as non-playing coach in 1947.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sporting Globe|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Rev. Doug. Nicholls to coach Northcote|page=4|date=25 January 1947}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career, particularly in the early years, Nicholls was subjected to onfield taunts or ostracised by his team-mates due to his colour. Nevertheless, he became a popular player among spectators; and, upon joining Fitzroy, when he was initially sitting by himself in the change rooms (due to this ostracism), he was befriended by [[Haydn Bunton, Sr.]] who ensured he was made welcome within the team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110679183 |title=A legend in his time. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |location=ACT |date=25 September 1971 |accessdate=24 August 2015 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australianrules.com.au/2003stories/buntonstory.html |title=Haydn Bunton \u2013 legend and myth |last=Mansell |first=Ken |date=17 June 2003 |accessdate=9 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726052821/http://australianrules.com.au/2003stories/buntonstory.html |archivedate=26 July 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLike his close relative [[Lynch Cooper]], Nicholls was also a very capable sprinter. He competed in gift races around Victoria during the athletics seasons, and in 1928 he won both the Nyah and Warracknabeal Gifts.<ref name=\"victor\" /> Following this, the race organisers paid him an appearance fee, board and expenses to enter races. He was the inaugural chairman of the National Aboriginal Sports Foundation.\n\nPlaying football provided employment during the winter. To earn a living during the rest of the year, he [[boxing|boxed]] with [[Jimmy Sharman]]'s Boxing Troupe, a travelling sideshow in which Sharman offered his fighters for challenge against all comers.\n\nDuring World War II, Nicholls was an adept [[boomerang]] thrower, teaching that skill to some members of the United States military. There is a photograph depicting this in the Australian War Memorial archives.<ref>[https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/141672/ Australian War Memorial website. |1944-09-04 Doug Nicholls, an Australian Aborigine and ex-Fitzroy footballer, demonstrating the art of throwing a boomerang to Lieutenant Colonel Forrest M.Carhartt of the United States Army.]</ref> He also organised and captained Aboriginal teams in football matches used for patriotic fundraisers during the war, many of which were played against Northcote.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Argus|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|title=Northcote to play against Aborigines|page=18|date=14 June 1946}}</ref>\n\n==The long road to the 1967 Referendum==\n[[File:President Patten (right) reads resolution (12097104296).jpg|thumb|Tom Foster, Jack Kinchela (obscured), Doug Nicholls, [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], and [[Jack Patten]] reading the resolution of the Aborigines Progressive Association at the All Australian Aboriginal Conference and Day of Mourning at Australian Hall, Sydney on 26 January 1938. ]]\n[[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], an uncle to Nicholls, mentored him in leadership, eventually placing him as the secretary of the [[Australian Aborigines' League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ia.anu.edu.au/biography/nicholls-sir-douglas-ralph-doug-14920|title=Biography - Sir Douglas Ralph (Doug) Nicholls - Indigenous Australia|website=ia.anu.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It was a founding principle of the League that Aboriginal Affairs was made a Federal matter, which would require a change in the [[Constitution of Australia]], which could only be effected by a referendum. As early as February 1935 Cooper, Nicholls and others were lobbying Members of Parliament, such as [[Thomas Paterson]], the Commonwealth minister for the interior on this issue. It gained national attention when Nicholls, leveraging his profile as a nationally famous athlete, participated in the [[Day of Mourning (Australia)|Day of Mourning]] protest for Aborigines held in Sydney on 26 January 1938, where Indigenous leaders from across the country made the demand to change the Constitution. The proposed resolution was: <blockquote>WE, representing THE ABORIGINES OF AUSTRALIA, assembled in conference at the Australian Hall, Sydney, on the 26th day of January, 1938, this being the 150th Anniversary of the Whiteman's seizure of our country, HEREBY MAKE PROTEST against the callous treatment of our people by the whitemen during the past 150 years, AND WE APPEAL to the Australian nation of today to make new laws for the education and care of Aborigines, we ask for a new policy which will raise our people TO FULL CITIZEN STATUS and EQUALITY WITHIN THE COMMUNITY.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/day-mourning-26th-january-1938|title=Day of Mourning - 26th January 1938|date=2018-01-08|website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> </blockquote>Doug Nicholls rose to support the resolution on behalf of the Victorian Aborigines League that day, saying:  <blockquote>On behalf of Victorian Aborigines I want to say that we support this resolution in every way. The public does not realise what our people have suffered for 150 years. Aboriginal girls have been sent to Aboriginal Reserves and have not been given any opportunity to improve themselves. Their treatment has been disgusting. The white people have done nothing for us whatever. Put on Reserves, with no proper education, how can Aborigines take their place as equals with whites? Now is our chance to have things altered. We must fight our very hardest in this cause. After 150 years our people are still bossed and influenced by white people. I know that we could proudly hold our own with others if given the chance. Do not let us forget, also, those of our own people who are still in a primitive state. It is for them that we should try to do something. We should all work in co-operation for the progress of Aborigines throughout the Commonwealth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.teachingheritage.nsw.edu.au/section07/wc2_1938speeches.php|title=- Board of Studies NSW|last=NSW|first=Board of Studies|last2=NSW|first2=Board of Studies|website=www.teachingheritage.nsw.edu.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Logo of the Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders.png|thumb|Nicholls was one of the founders of the Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]]\nThe movement took 30 years to coalesce and achieve anything like its stated goal, but it soon made its focus the Constitution of Australia which, in its original form, prevented the Commonwealth from making any law that would benefit the Aboriginal people. In 1949, a letter written by Nicholls prompted the Labor MP, [[Kim Beazley Sr.]] to write to Prime Minister [[Ben Chifley]] asking him to explore how the Constitution could be amended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au/learningobjects/Content/R10908/object/r11027.html|title=Doug Nicholls|website=tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In 1957, [[Jessie Street]] approached Nicholls about brining in the Victorian Aboriginal Advancement League to form a federal council to campaign for Aboriginal affairs to become a federal matter \u2014 this would became the [[Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]]. Its early work involved drafting and collecting petitions, from suburbs and town centres from across the country. By 1962 they had achieved 100,000 signatures<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tlf.dlr.det.nsw.edu.au/learningobjects/Content/R10908/object/r7882.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=NSW Department of Education and Training|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> with the stated goal of 250,000 signatures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nma.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/692620/goal-of-250000-signatures.pdf|title=250,000 Signatures to be sought on Native-Rights Petition|last=|first=|date=October 2, 1962|website=National Museum of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The movement supporting a change to the constitution, which removed the block on the Federal Government making a laws regarding Aboriginal people, soon became known as the \"yes\" campaign.  \n[[File:Harold Holt and FCAATSI.jpg|thumb|Pastor Doug Nicholls in a meeting Prime Minister Harold Holt, three months before the 1967 referendum. With him are several members of (FCAATSI) \u2013 from left to right: Gordon Bryant, Faith Bandler, Harold Holt, Doug Nicholls, Burnum Burnum, Winnie Branson, and Bill Wentworth.]]\nFCAATSI would later became the central lobby group who were able to interface with the Federal Government. During this time Pastor Doug was known to have met and negotiated with Prime Ministers [[Robert Menzies]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Harold Holt]]. However, creating the political momentum involved substantial grass roots action. Nicholls' daughter, Pam recalls her father winning support from white Australians at football games: <blockquote>\u201cWith his friend Alick Jackomos, they used to have a card table and go and sit outside the football giving out papers, giving speeches, beckoning people to come sign the petitions for the \u2018yes\u2019 vote.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Riordan|first=Primrose|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/1967-indigenous-referendum-citizenship-one-footy-fan-at-a-time/news-story/e4edbc62a7e534a1f05ed79ae0da491e|title=1967 indigenous referendum: citizenship, one footy fan at a time|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>Nicholls interacted with the media frequently. Drawing on his abilities as a preacher, he was able to deliver pithy, persuasive messages which were effective in winning over the Australian public. One common line of argument he made was for the \"Yes\" vote was:<blockquote>\u201cI think it\u2019s a matter of democratic right. And we will form a part of the British commonwealth of nations and there should be no legislation setup to discriminate us.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aikman|first=Amos|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/how-the-1967-referendum-unfolded/news-story/c20726a61f4c0f769f80c48af67ccc4e|title=How the 1967 referendum unfolded|date=May 27, 2017|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>The [[1967 Australian referendum]] was an emphatic success for Nicholls and the FCAATSI leadership, with an average of 90% of Australians<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/right-wrongs-write-yes-what-was-the-1967-referendum-all-about-76512|title=\u2018Right wrongs, write Yes\u2019: what was the 1967 referendum all about?|last=McGregor|first=Russell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> supporting the change they had asked for. Following the successful outcome of the referendum, Pastor Doug argued that much more than a legal change had been made, rather, it was:<blockquote>\u2026 evidence that Australians recognise Aborigines are part of the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/right-wrongs-write-yes-what-was-the-1967-referendum-all-about-76512|title=\u2018Right wrongs, write Yes\u2019: what was the 1967 referendum all about?|last=McGregor|first=Russell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Community work and Christian ministry==\nNicholls was a minister and [[social work]]er with [[Australian Aborigine|Aboriginal people]]. Following his mother's death he took a renewed interest in Christianity and was baptised at Northcote [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Church of Christ]] (now Northern Community Church of Christ) in 1935. He officiated at church and hymn services as a [[lay preacher]] at the Gore Street Mission Centre in [[Fitzroy, Victoria|Fitzroy]].\n\nIn 1941 Nicholls received his call-up notice and he joined the [[2/29th Battalion (Australia)|29th Battalion]] but, in 1942, at the request of the Fitzroy police, he was released from his unit to work as a [[social worker]] in the Fitzroy Aboriginal community. He cared for those trapped in [[alcohol abuse]], gambling, and other social problems, and those who were in trouble with the police. Indigenous people gathered to him and eventually the group was so large that he became the pastor of the first Aboriginal [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Church of Christ]] in Australia. In recognition of the ministry he was already expressing, he was ordained as a minister.\n\nIn a letter to the editor, in 1953, it was noted that Opposition Leader, [[H. V. Evatt]], had asked the Prime Minister [[Robert Menzies]], on 26 February, in Federal Parliament, 'for an invitation to be extended to Capt. Reg Saunders or some other outstanding representative of the aborigines' to be included in the official [[Australia]]n contingent to the [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|coronation]] of [[Elizabeth II]]. The author suggested Nicholls, as an ordained minister, and for his community work in the areas of [[Fitzroy, Victoria|Fitzroy]] and [[Mooroopna, Victoria|Mooroopna]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64434531 |title=ABORIGINE FOR CORONATION?. |newspaper=[[Portland Guardian|Portland Guardian (Vic. : 1876 - 1953)]] |location=Vic. |date=16 April 1953 |accessdate=27 September 2013 |page=4 Edition: MIDDAY |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957 Nicholls became a field officer for the [[Aborigines Advancement League]]. He edited their magazine, ''Smoke Signals'', and helped draw Aboriginal issues to the attention of Government officials and the general public. He pleaded for dignity for Aboriginal people as human beings. Support for the AAL grew rapidly.\n\nNicholls helped set up hostels for Aboriginal children, holiday homes for Aboriginal people at [[Queenscliff, Victoria|Queenscliff]] and was a founding member and Victorian Secretary of the [[Federal Council for the Advancement of Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders]] (FCAATSI). In response to protests in the 1950s and 60s for an independent, Aboriginal-run farming cooperative at [[Lake Tyers Mission]] he campaigned on their behalf, but when the board moved to close Lake Tyers, Nichols resigned his position in protest.<ref name=\"ABC\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-21/lake-tyers-history-piece/5170896 A brief history of the Lake Tyers Aboriginal community, By Jeff Waters, ABC Radio, 21 Dec 2013]</ref>\n\nNicholls was an active [[Freemasonry|Freemason]].<ref name=\"bio\">[http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Indigenous/BIOGRAPHIES_FOR_NICHOLLS.DOC Biographies of Doug and Gladys Nicholls] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730211511/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Indigenous/BIOGRAPHIES_FOR_NICHOLLS.DOC |date=30 July 2008 }}, Council of Melbourne (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref>\n\n==Governor of South Australia==\n[[File:Douglas Nicholls 1977.jpg|thumb|Pastor Sir Douglas Nicholls is sworn in as Governor of South Australia, in front of Premier Don Dunstan and other dignitaries 1977]]\nNicholls was appointed [[Governor of South Australia]] on 1 December 1976, on the nomination of Premier [[Don Dunstan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131798665|title=Historic, says Sir Douglas|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=2 December 1976}}</ref> He was the first non-white person to serve as the governor of an Australian state, and is the only Aboriginal person to have held viceregal office. Because of his race, his nomination proved controversial and attracted more attention than most viceregal appointments. A poll by ABC's ''[[This Day Tonight]]'' found that 70 percent of respondents opposed Nicholls becoming governor. ''[[The Canberra Times]]'' expressed concern that members of his family might set up camp on the grounds of [[Government House, Adelaide|Government House]]. However, Adelaide's main daily newspaper ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' was more positive, welcoming the news \"without reservation\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819165|title=Next Governor may test community's racial tolerance|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=25 May 1976}}</ref> News of the appointment was leaked in May 1976, after which he agreed to appear on ''[[A Current Affair (Australian TV program)|A Current Affair]]''. Nicholls took exception to a question directed at his wife, calling the interviewer a racist and requiring him to leave his house.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819394|title=Sir Douglas angered|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=26 May 1976}}</ref> [[GTV (Australia)|GTV-9]] aired the footage without his permission, and subsequently apologised for doing so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/131819719|title=Apology|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=27 May 1976}}</ref>\n\nNicholls' predecessor as governor, nuclear physicist [[Mark Oliphant]], confidentially wrote to the state government expressing concerns about the appointment. He said there were \"grave dangers\" involved, as \"there is something inherent in the personality of the Aborigine which makes it difficult for him to adapt fully to the ways of the white man\".<ref name=\"Black\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Age]] |date=20 August 1981 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19810820&id=6zJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h5QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3739,1176081 |title=Oliphant did not want Black |accessdate=7 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511050518/https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19810820&id=6zJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h5QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3739,1176081 |archive-date=11 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 1977, Nicholls suffered a stroke and was admitted to the cardiac ward at [[Royal Adelaide Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110837268|title=Sir Douglas Nicholls in hospital|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=26 January 1977}}</ref> He had a history of high blood pressure and had suffered a mild heart attack some years earlier.<ref name=resign>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110733486|title=Nicholls to resign as SA Governor|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=19 April 1977}}</ref> He was not discharged until three weeks later,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110841256|title=Discharged|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=16 February 1977}}</ref> with Lieutenant-Governor [[Walter Crocker]] serving as [[Administrator (Australia)|Administrator of the Government]] in his place.<ref name=resign/> Nicholls attended only one further official engagement after his stroke, hosting Queen [[Elizabeth II]] at Government House on 20 March.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110729441 The Canberra Times], 21 March 1977.</ref> She subsequently awarded him a second knighthood, [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO).<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110729930 The Canberra Times], 24 March 1977</ref> Nicholls' retirement due to ill health was announced on 22 April, with effect from 30 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110734432|title=Governor officially resigns|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=23 April 1977}}</ref> He held office for only 150 days, making him the shortest-serving governor in South Australian history and the only governor to serve for less than a year.\n\n==Family==\nIn December 1942 Nicholls married [[Gladys Nicholls]], the widow of his brother Howard Nicholls (1905\u20131942); Howard (who had married Gladys in 1927) had died in April 1942 as a result of injuries sustained in a car accident. Gladys already had three children. Douglas Nicholls and Gladys were married for 39 years and raised their combined six children; two sons, Bevan and Ralph, and four daughters, Beryl, Nora, Lilian and Pamela.<ref name=\"bio\" /> Lady Gladys Nicholls died in 1981.\n\nNicholls' great grandson [[Nathan Lovett-Murray]] also played [[Australian Rules Football]], playing 145 games for [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]].<ref>http://australianfootball.com/players/player/nathan%2Blovett-murray/14592</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Pastor Sir Douglas and Lady Gladys Nicholls Memorial.jpg|thumb|300px|Statue in Parliament Gardens, [[East Melbourne, Victoria]]]]\n* 1957 \u2013 appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE).\n* 1962 \u2013 chosen by the Father's Day Council of Australia as Victoria's Father of the Year for \"outstanding leadership in youth and welfare work and for the inspired example he set the community in his unfailing efforts to further the cause of the Australian Aborigine\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fathersdaycouncil.org.au/past-winners/|title=Past winners|date=2012-05-08|work=Father's Day Council of Victoria Inc.|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* 1968 \u2013 promoted to Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE).\n* 1970 \u2013 among Victorians invited guests to greet [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] on her visit to Australia.\n* 1972 \u2013 first Aboriginal to be knighted when he was appointed [[Knight Bachelor]];<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1083655&search_type=advanced&showInd=true Knight Bachelor] itsanhonour.gov.au</ref> he and his wife Gladys travelled to London to receive that honour.<ref name=\"pressreader.com\"/>\n* 1973 \u2013 appointed [[Moomba|King of Moomba]].<ref>Craig Bellamy, Gordon Chisholm, Hilary Eriksen (17 February 2006) ''Moomba: A festival for the people.'': {{cite web|url=http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Moomba/History%20of%20Moomba.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028203816/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/rsrc/PDFs/Moomba/History%20of%20Moomba.pdf |archivedate=28 October 2009}} PDF pp 17\u201322 also p 8 for photo</ref>\n* 1976 \u2013 appointed the 28th Governor of South Australia, the first Aboriginal person appointed to vice-regal office.\n* 1977 \u2013 appointed a Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (KCVO)<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1082642&search_type=advanced&showInd=true KCVO] itsanhonour.gov.au</ref>\n* 1991 \u2013 the [[Canberra]] suburb of [[Nicholls, Australian Capital Territory|Nicholls]] was named after him\n* 2001 \u2013 a new chapel in Preston of the Northern Community Church of Christ, the church in which he was baptized, is named after him.\n* 2006 \u2013 to commemorate the centenary of his birth, a statue of Nicholls, one-and-a-half times life size, was approved for the Parliament Gardens, beside the Parliament of Victoria;<ref>[http://one.melbourne.vic.gov.au/opm/bc/CTEE/meetings/EC_34_200605160700.pdf Memorial for Pastor Sir Doug and Lady Nicholls]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, submission by Assets and Services Division, Council of Melbourne, 16 May 2006 (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref> it was officially opened in December 2007<ref>[http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/info.cfm?top=251&pg=2045 City of Melbourne \u2013 Walks and tours \u2013 Sir Douglas and Lady Gladys Nicholls Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013050015/http://www.melbourne.vic.gov.au/info.cfm?top=251&pg=2045 |date=13 October 2007 }}, City of Melbourne (accessed 14 January 2008)</ref> and was the first statue of an Aboriginal erected in Victoria.\n*2011 \u2013 inducted to Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vic.gov.au/aboriginalvictoria/community-engagement/leadership-programs/aboriginal-honour-roll/2011-victorian-aboriginal-honour-roll.html|title=2011 Victorian Aboriginal Honour Roll|website=www.vic.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> \n* 2016 \u2013 The [[Australian Football League|AFL]] named their \"[[Indigenous round]]\" after him, and continue to do so.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/28/afl-to-honour-sir-doug-nicholls-in-2016-indigenous-round AFL to honour Sir Doug Nicholls in 2016 Indigenous round], [[The Guardian]], 28 October 2015</ref><ref name=Guard>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/28/afl-to-honour-sir-doug-nicholls-in-2016-indigenous-round|title=AFL to honour Sir Doug Nicholls in 2016 Indigenous round|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> Each year, each player in all 18 clubs wears a specially-commissioned artwork by an Indigenous artist on their guernsey.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/afl-indigenous-guernseys-revealed-and-the-stories-behind-them-20190521-p51pme.html|newspaper=The Age|title=AFL Indigenous guernseys revealed, and the stories behind them|first=Charlotte|last=Grieve|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 The federal electoral division of Murray is renamed Nicholls in honour of Sir Doug and Lady Nicholls.<ref>https://www.sheppnews.com.au/@news/2018/06/29/135789/xx-3</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 a [[Google Doodle]] was created to celebrate his 112th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/sir-douglas-nicholls-112th-birthday |title=Sir Douglas Nicholls' 112th Birthday |website=www.google.com |language=en |access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Doug Nicholls Grave IMG 0977.jpg|thumb|Grave of Douglas and Gladys Nicholls at Cummeragunja Cemetery]] [[File:Doug Nicholas Grave IMG 0978.jpg|thumb|Headstone of grave of Doug Nicholls and his wife]]\n\n==Death==\nNicholls died on 4 June 1988 at Mooroopna. A [[state funeral]] was held for him and he was buried in the cemetery at Cummeragunja.<ref name=adb-bio/>\n\n==Sources==\n* Clark, M. (1972) ''Pastor Doug'', Lansdowne Press, Melbourne. {{ISBN|0-7018-0017-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120717070313/http://www.kooriweb.org/foley/heroes/nicholls.html Biography of Sir Douglas Nicholls (Pastor)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050624192309/http://www.decc.org.au/fourteen.htm Biography of Douglas Nicholls at Darebin Ethnic Communities Council site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050417170027/http://abc.net.au/missionvoices/cummeragunja/default.htm ABC Mission Voices \u2013 Cummeragunja. Koorie Heritage Trust]\n* [http://www.michaelwinkler.com.au/PDF/The%20great%20Pastor%20Sir%20Doug%20Nicholls.pdf The Great Australian: Pastor Sir Doug Nicholls]\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=D/Doug_Nicholls.html}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Mark Oliphant|Sir Mark Oliphant]] |\n  after=[[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] |\n  title=[[Governor of South Australia]] |\n  years=1976\u20131977\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of South Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicholls, Douglas}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Christian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian players of Australian rules football]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian boxers]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Fitzroy Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Northcote Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Northcote Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Tongala Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Australian Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Australian members of the Churches of Christ]]\n[[Category:Australian male boxers]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Bachelor]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "not salty", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Douglas_Nicholls"}
{"title_page": "Evil Empire (album)", "text_new": "{{about||the phrase used by U.S. president Ronald Reagan to describe the U.S.S.R.|Evil Empire speech||Evil empire (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Evil Empire\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Rage Against the Machine]]\n| cover      = Rage Against the Machine - Evil Empire.png\n| alt        = cover illustration derived from \"Crimebuster\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1996|04|16}}\n| recorded   = March 1995\u2013February 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Cole Rehearsal Studios, [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| genre      = [[Rap metal]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Lipkin|first=Gregg|date=November 18, 2009|url=http://www.popmatters.com/post/116195-masters-of-the-form-rage-against-the-machine-1996-evil-empire/|title=Masters of the Form: Rage Against the Machine 1996 - Evil Empire|work=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=46|s=37}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]]\n| prev_title = [[Rage Against the Machine (album)|Rage Against the Machine]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[The Battle of Los Angeles (album)|The Battle of Los Angeles]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Evil Empire\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Year of tha Boomerang]]\n | single1date = December 17, 1994\n | single2     = [[Bulls on Parade]]\n | single2date = February 9, 1996\n | single3     = [[People of the Sun]]\n | single3date = August 22, 1996\n | single4     = [[Down Rodeo]]\n | single4date = November 16, 1996\n | single5     = [[Vietnow]]\n | single5date = October 10, 1997\n}}\n}}\n'''''Evil Empire''''' is the second studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Rage Against the Machine]], released on April 16, 1996 by [[Epic Records]]. Its title refers to a [[Evil Empire speech|term]] used in the early 1980s by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and many [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatives]] to describe the former [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"mtv1996\">Staff report (May 3, 1996). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1433600/19960503/rage_against_the_machine.jhtml Rage Builds \"Evil Empire\"] [[MTV]]</ref>\n\n''Evil Empire'' debuted at number 1 on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], and their song \"[[Tire Me]]\" won a 1996 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance]]; \"[[Bulls on Parade]]\" and \"[[People of the Sun]]\" were also nominated for Grammys for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]]. The album was certified [[RIAA certification|3x platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] on May 24, 2000.<ref>[[RIAA]] [https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH RIAA Certification search results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626000000/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |date=June 26, 2007 }} Note: type \u201cEvil Empire\u201d (without quotation marks) in field \"Title:\"</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{cquote|''The title \"Evil Empire\" is taken from what Rage Against The Machine see as Ronald Reagan's slander of the Soviet Union in the eighties, which the band feels could just as easily apply to the United States. Rage is currently finishing up a European tour but they'll be back on our evil U.S. soil for a tour in late July.''\n|4=[[Zack de la Rocha]]\n|5=excerpt from interview<ref>{{cite web|last=de la Rocha|first=Zacar\u00edas Manuel \"Zack\"|title=Rage Builds \"Evil Empire\"|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1433600/rage-builds-evil-empire.jhtml|work=MTV|publisher=MTV.com|accessdate=7 April 2013|date=May 3, 1996|quote=The title \"Evil Empire\" is taken from what Rage Against The Machine see as Ronald Reagan's slander of the Soviet Union in the eighties, which the band feels could just as easily apply to the United States. Rage is currently finishing up a European tour but they'll be back on our evil U.S. soil for a tour in late July.}}</ref>}}\n\nDe la Rocha expands further on the UK CD single release of \"Bulls on Parade\" explaining how America (the U.S.), is building a wall between itself and [[Mexico]].\n\n{{cquote|''\u2026the wall that Germany fell and the US Government was busy building another one between the border of the U.S. and Mexico. Since 1986, as a result of a lot of the hate talk and hysteria, that the Government of the United States has been speaking, 1,500 bodies have been found on the border; we wrote this song in response to it.''}}\n\nThe cover features an altered version by [[Mel Ramos]] of the 1940s\u20131950s comicbook hero [[Crimebuster (Boy Comics)|Crimebuster]], with his emblem changed to a lowercase \"e\".<ref>Rage Against The Machine \u201cEvil Empire\u201d Album Cover Art Was Originally Called \u201cCrime Buster\u201d.[http://www.feelnumb.com/2011/01/11/rage-against-the-machine-evil-empire-album-cover-art-was-called-crime-buster/]\n</ref><ref>Mark Malazarte [http://waxinandmilkin.com/post/248742034/crime-buster-by-mel-ramos-1993 ''Crime Buster'' by Mel Ramos 1993]</ref> Additional themes for the album were created by [[Barbara Kruger]], and some of her artwork appears in the video clip for \"[[Bulls on Parade]]\", which became the second single for the album. As with their debut, five singles were released in total.\n\nThe inside of the CD booklet shows a picture of a pile of various political and philosophical books, which include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ratm.net/book.html|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117050008/http://www.ratm.net/book.html|archivedate=2011-11-17|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref>\n\n* ''[[A People's History of the United States]]'' by [[Howard Zinn]]\n* ''[[Capital, Volume I]]'' by [[Karl Marx]] \n* ''[[A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man]]'' by [[James Joyce]]\n* ''[[The Anarchist Cookbook]]'' by William Powell\n* [[Guerrilla Warfare (book)|''Guerrilla Warfare'']] by [[Che Guevara]]\n* ''[[Revolutionary Suicide]]'' by [[Huey P. Newton]]\n* ''[[Soul on Ice (book)|Soul on Ice]]'' by [[Eldridge Cleaver]]\n* ''[[The Wretched of the Earth]]'' by [[Frantz Fanon]]\n* ''[[Darkness at Noon]]'' by [[Arthur Koestler]]\n* ''[[Manufacturing Consent: The Political Economy of the Mass Media]]'' by ''[[Edward S. Herman]] and [[Noam Chomsky]]''\n* ''[[Live from Death Row]]'' by ''[[Mumia Abu-Jamal]]''\n* ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]'' by ''[[Dalton Trumbo]]''\n* ''[[Now and After|Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism]]'' by ''[[Alexander Berkman]]''\n* ''[[The Grapes of Wrath]]'' by [[John Steinbeck]]\n* ''[[Rules for Radicals]]'' by [[Saul Alinsky|Saul D. Alinsky]]\n* ''Soledad Brother: The Prison Letters of George Jackson'' by [[George Jackson (Black Panther)|George Jackson]]\n* ''[[Walden]] and [[Civil Disobedience (Thoreau)|Resistance to Civil Government]]'' by [[Henry David Thoreau]]\n* ''[[Invisible Man]]'' by [[Ralph Ellison]]\n* ''[[Another Country (novel)|Another Country]]'' by [[James Baldwin]]\n\n==Promotion==\nIn 1995, the band sent a free 7\u2033 record to everyone who signed up for the fan club promoted in the liner notes of their debut. Doubling as an apology to those who had received nothing and a promotion for the upcoming album, it came in a plain cardboard colored fold-out with a black-and-white American flag on the cover and the title \"Evil Empire\" and the band's name all in capitals. On the back was a [[Universal Product Code|UPC]] with marker scribble on the barcode. The A-side was a reissue of the [[Steve Lamacq|\"Evening Session\"]] version of \"Bombtrack\", listed as \"Bombtrack (Live on the [[BBC]])\". The B-side was a then unreleased cover of [[N.W.A]]'s \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", recorded live on August 13, 1995 at a benefit concert for [[Mumia Abu-Jamal]] at the Capitol Ballroom in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/evil-empire-mw0000647704|title=Evil Empire \u2013 Rage Against the Machine|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 15, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-04-25/features/9604250332_1_evil-empire-zack-de-la-rocha-pit-bull|title=Saved By a Guitar|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=April 25, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|url=https://ew.com/article/1996/04/19/evil-empire/|title=Evil Empire|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=April 19, 1996|accessdate=February 15, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021234948/https://ew.com/article/1996/04/19/evil-empire/|archivedate=October 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Chirazi|first=Steffan|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/article/POP-CDS-Richard-Thompson-Broods-And-Rocks-on-2986404.php|title=Rage Keeps Politics, Adds Stronger Music|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=April 14, 1996|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Cromelin|first=Richard|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-04-14/entertainment/ca-58322_1_album-review|title=Rage Against the Machine 'Evil Empire' Epic|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 14, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cigarettes|first=Johnny|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000673reviews.html|title=Rage Against the Machine \u2013 Evil Empire|journal=[[NME]]|date=April 13, 1996|accessdate=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817181817/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000673reviews.html|archivedate=August 17, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 6.1/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Schreiber|first=Ryan|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/r/rage-against-the-machine/evil-empire.shtml|title=Rage Against The Machine: Evil Empire|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=April 1996|accessdate=December 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051031192802/http://pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/r/rage-against-the-machine/evil-empire.shtml|archivedate=October 31, 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/evil-empire-19960418|title=Evil Empire|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 18, 1996|accessdate=March 7, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gold|first=Jonathan|authorlink=Jonathan Gold|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXQ6nPE3H9wC&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103|title=Rage Against the Machine: Evil Empire|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|volume=12|issue=2|date=May 1996|accessdate=March 7, 2012|page=103}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv796-96.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|date=July 23, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\"This music isn't supposed to be fun,\" noted ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. \"Rage Against the Machine have jacked up the [[political sociology|sociopolitical]] [[siege mentality]] in their [[Rap rock|metallic hip-hop]] to such a [[dogma]]tic degree \u2013 and honed their sound to such maniacally shrill perfection \u2013 that the band and the roaring joys of its harangue 'n' roll seem virtually [[Asexuality|sexless]].\"<ref>''[[Rolling Stone]] Yearbook'', 26 December 1996\u20139 January 1997</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 46:34\n\n| all_lyrics      = [[Zack de la Rocha]]\n| all_music       = [[Rage Against the Machine]]\n\n| title1          = [[People of the Sun]]\n| length1         = 2:30\n\n| title2          = [[Bulls on Parade]]\n| length2         = 3:49\n\n| title3          = [[Vietnow]]\n| length3         = 4:39\n\n| title4          = Revolver\n| length4         = 5:30\n\n| title5          = Snakecharmer\n| length5         = 3:56\n\n| title6          = [[Tire Me]]\n| length6         = 3:00\n\n| title7          = [[Down Rodeo]]\n| length7         = 5:20\n\n| title8          = Without a Face\n| length8         = 3:36\n\n| title9          = Wind Below\n| length9         = 5:50\n\n| title10         = Roll Right\n| length10        = 4:22\n\n| title11         = [[Year of tha Boomerang]]\n| length11        = 4:02\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Rage Against the Machine'''\n* [[Zack de la Rocha]] &ndash; [[vocals]]\n* [[Tom Morello]] &ndash; [[electric guitar|guitars]]\n* [[Tim Commerford]] (credited as \"Tim Bob\") &ndash; [[bass guitar|bass]]\n* [[Brad Wilk]] &ndash; [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n'''Technical'''\n* [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]] &ndash; [[Record producer|production]]\n* Rage Against the Machine &ndash; co-production\n* [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] &ndash; [[Audio mixing|mixing]]\n* Nick DiDia &ndash; [[Audio engineer|engineering]], recording\n* Caram Costanzo &ndash; engineering\n* Clay Harper &ndash; assistant engineering\n* [[Dave Rat]] &ndash; recording <small>(\"[[Down Rodeo]]\" vocals)</small>\n* Paul Kosky &ndash; recording <small>(\"Down Rodeo\" vocals)</small>\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] &ndash; [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n\n'''Artwork and design'''\n* Rage Against the Machine &ndash; art direction\n* Aim\u00e9e Macauley &ndash; art direction\n* [[Lisa Johnson]] &ndash; photography\n\n===Recording locations===\n* Cole Rehearsal Studios, [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, CA]] &ndash; recording\n* Kiss Music Recording Studios, [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] &ndash; recording <small>(\"Down Rodeo\" vocals)</small>\n* The Enterprise &ndash; [[Audio mixing|mixing]]\n* Gateway Mastering Studios &ndash; [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Album===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Australia|2|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Austria|2|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Flanders|6|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Wallonia|2|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|Danish Albums ([[Hitlisten]])<ref name=\"Listen\">{{cite news |title=Listen - Danmarks Officielle Hitliste - Udarbejdet af AIM Nielsen for IFPI Danmark - Uge 16 |work=[[Ekstra Bladet]] |location=[[Copenhagen]] |language=Danish |date=1996-04-21 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Netherlands|4|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Finland|5|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|France|1<ref>http://www.infodisc.fr/Album_ChartRuns_Liste.php</ref>|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Germany|2|artist=Rage Against the Machine}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|New Zealand|3|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Norway|2|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|Spanish Albums ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002|edition=1st|date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Sweden|1|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Switzerland|4|artist=Rage Against the Machine|album=Evil Empire}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|UK|4|artist=Rage Against the Machine}}\n|-\n{{Albumchart|UKRock|1|date=19960421}}\n|-\n|{{Album chart|Billboard200|1|artist=Rage Against the Machine|artistid=277341}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"column\"|Chart (1996)\n!scope=\"column\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|German Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/album-jahr/for-date-1996 |title=Top 100 Album-Jahrescharts|language=German |publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|41\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Single\n! Chart\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" | \"[[Bulls on Parade]]\"\n|{{singlechart|Australia|29|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Wallonia|31|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Dutch100|46|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|France|27|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|New Zealand|22|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Norway|4|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Sweden|9|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|UK|8|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=Bulls on Parade|date=1996-04-13|refname=\"Bulls UK single chart}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|11|artist=Rage Against the Machine}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|36|artist=Rage Against the Machine}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardradiosongs|62|artist=Rage Against the Machine}}\n|-\n| \"[[People of the Sun]]\"\n|{{singlechart|UK|26|artist=Rage Against the Machine|song=People of the Sun|date=1996-09-07|refname=\"People UK single chart}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Belgium|artist=Rage Against the Machine|title=Evil Empire|relyear=1996|certyear=1996|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|artist=Rage Against the Machine|title=Evil Empire|relyear=1996|type=album|award=Platinum}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Spain|artist=Rage Against the Machine|title=Evil Empire|award=Gold|type=album|relyear=1996|certyear=1996|certref=<ref>{{cite book |last=Salaverrie |first=Fernando |date=September 2005 |url=http://www.mediafire.com/file/pd758fesp2w7i7f/Spanish+Certifications+for+1996-1999.pdf |title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002 |language=Spanish |edition=1st |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Sociedad General de Autores y Editores|Fundaci\u00f3n Autor/SGAE]] |page=940 |isbn=84-8048-639-2 |accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=Rage Against the Machine|title=Evil Empire|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Rage Against the Machine|title=Evil Empire|type=album|award=Platinum|number=3}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Awards==\n* [[38th Annual Grammy Awards|1996]] [[Grammy Award]] - Best Metal Performance for \"Tire Me\"\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ronald Reagan in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmusic |class=album |id=mw0000647704 |label=''Evil Empire''}}\n\n{{Rage Against the Machine}}\n\n[[Category:1996 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Brendan O'Brien (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Rage Against the Machine albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the phrase used by U.S. president Ronald Reagan to describe the U.S.S.R.|Evil Empire speech||Evil empire (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Evil Empire\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Rage Against the Machine]]\n| cover      = Rage Against the Machine - Evil Empire.png\n| alt        = cover illustration derived from \"Crimebuster\"\n| released   = {{Start date|1996|04|16}}\n| recorded   = March 1995\u2013February 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Cole Rehearsal Studios, [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| genre      = [[Rap metal]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Lipkin|first=Gregg|date=November 18, 2009|url=http://www.popmatters.com/post/116195-masters-of-the-form-rage-against-the-machine-1996-evil-empire/|title=Masters of the Form: Rage Against the Machine 1996 - Evil Empire|work=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=46|s=37}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]]\n| prev_title = [[Rage Against the Machine (album)|Rage Against the Machine]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[The Battle of Los Angeles (album)|The Battle of Los Angeles]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Evil Empire\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Year of tha Boomerang]]\n | single1date = December 17, 1994\n | single2     = [[Bulls on Parade]]\n | single2date = February 9, 1996\n | single3     = [[People of the Sun]]\n | single3date = August 22, 1996\n | single4     = [[Down Rodeo]]\n | single4date = November 16, 1996\n | single5     = [[Vietnow]]\n | single5date = October 10, 1997\n}}\n}}\n'''''Evil Empire''''' is the second studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Rage Against the Machine]], released on April 16, 1996 by [[Epic Records]]. Its title refers to a [[Evil Empire speech|term]] used in the early 1980s by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and many [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatives]] to describe the former [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"mtv1996\">Staff report (May 3, 1996). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1433600/19960503/rage_against_the_machine.jhtml Rage Builds \"Evil Empire\"] [[MTV]]</ref>\n\n''Evil Empire'' debuted at number 1 on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], and their song \"[[Tire Me]]\" won a 1996 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance]]; \"[[Bulls on Parade]]\" and \"[[People of the Sun]]\" were also nominated for Grammys for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]]. The album was certified [[RIAA certification|3x platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] on May 24, 2000.<ref>[[RIAA]] [https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH RIAA Certification search results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626000000/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |date=June 26, 2007 }} Note: type \u201cEvil Empire\u201d (without quotation marks) in field \"Title:\"</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{cquote|''The title \"Evil Empire\" is taken from what Rage Against The Machine see as Ronald Reagan's slander of the Soviet Union in the eighties, which the band feels could just as easily apply to the United States. Rage is currently finishing up a European tour but they'll be back on our evil U.S. soil for a tour in late July.''\n|4=[[Zack de la Rocha]]\n|5=excerpt from interview<ref>{{cite web|last=de la Rocha|first=Zacar\u00edas Manuel \"Zack\"|title=Rage Builds \"Evil Empire\"|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1433600/rage-builds-evil-empire.jhtml|work=MTV|publisher=MTV.com|accessdate=7 April 2013|date=May 3, 1996|quote=The title \"Evil Empire\" is taken from what Rage Against The Machine see as Ronald Reagan's slander of the Soviet Union in the eighties, which the band feels could just as easily apply to the United States. Rage is currently finishing up a European tour but they'll be back on our evil U.S. soil for a tour in late July.}}</ref>}}\n\nDe la Rocha expands further on the UK CD single release of \"Bulls on Parade\" explaining how America (the U.S.), is building a wall between itself and [[Mexico]].\n\n{{cquote|''\u2026the wall that Germany fell and the US Government was busy building another one between the border of the U.S. and Mexico. Since 1986, as a result of a lot of the hate talk and hysteria, that the Government of the United States has been speaking, 1,500 bodies have been found on the border; we wrote this song in response to it.''}}\n\nThe cover features an altered version by [[Mel Ramos]] of the 1940s\u20131950s comicbook hero [[Crimebuster (Boy Comics)|Crimebuster]], with his emblem changed to a lowercase \"e\".<ref>Rage Against The Machine \u201cEvil Empire\u201d Album Cover Art Was Originally Called \u201cCrime Buster\u201d.[http://www.feelnumb.com/2011/01/11/rage-against-the-machine-evil-empire-album-cover-art-was-called-crime-buster/]\n</ref><ref>Mark Malazarte [http://waxinandmilkin.com/post/248742034/crime-buster-by-mel-ramos-1993 ''Crime Buster'' by Mel Ramos 1993]</ref> Additional themes for the album were created by [[Barbara Kruger]], and some of her artwork appears in the video clip for \"[[Bulls on Parade]]\", which became the second single for the album. As with their debut, five singles were released in total.\n\nThe inside of the CD booklet shows a picture of a pile of various political and philosophical books, which include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ratm.net/book.html|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117050008/http://www.ratm.net/book.html|archivedate=2011-11-17|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref>\n\n* ''[[A People's History of the United States]]'' by [[Howard Zinn]]\n* ''[[Capital, Volume I]]'' by [[Karl Marx]] \n* ''[[A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man]]'' by [[James Joyce]]\n* ''[[The Anarchist Cookbook]]'' by William Powell\n* [[Guerrilla Warfare (book)|''Guerrilla Warfare'']] by [[Che Guevara]]\n* ''[[Revolutionary Suicide]]'' by [[Huey P. Newton]]\n* ''[[Soul on Ice (book)|Soul on Ice]]'' by [[Eldridge Cleaver]]\n* ''[[The Wretched of the Earth]]'' by [[Frantz Fanon]]\n* ''[[Darkness at Noon]]'' by [[Arthur Koestler]]\n* ''[[Manufacturing Consent: The Political Economy of the Mass Media]]'' by ''[[Edward S. Herman]] and [[Noam Chomsky]]''\n* ''[[Live from Death Row]]'' by ''[[Mumia Abu-Jamal]]''\n* ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]'' by ''[[Dalton Trumbo]]''\n* ''[[Now and After|Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism]]'' by ''[[Alexander Berkman]]''\n* ''[[The Grapes of Wrath]]'' by [[John Steinbeck]]\n* ''[[Rules for Radicals]]'' by [[Saul Alinsky|Saul D. Alinsky]]\n* ''Soledad Brother: The Prison Letters of George Jackson'' by [[George Jackson (Black Panther)|George Jackson]]\n* ''[[Walden]] and [[Civil Disobedience (Thoreau)|Resistance to Civil Government]]'' by [[Henry David Thoreau]]\n* ''[[Invisible Man]]'' by [[Ralph Ellison]]\n* ''[[Another Country (novel)|Another Country]]'' by [[James Baldwin]]\n\n==Promotion==\nIn 1995, the band sent a free 7\u2033 record to everyone who signed up for the fan club promoted in the liner notes of their debut. Doubling as an apology to those who had received nothing and a promotion for the upcoming album, it came in a plain cardboard colored fold-out with a black-and-white American flag on the cover and the title \"Evil Empire\" and the band's name all in capitals. On the back was a [[Universal Product Code|UPC]] with marker scribble on the barcode. The A-side was a reissue of the [[Steve Lamacq|\"Evening Session\"]] version of \"Bombtrack\", listed as \"Bombtrack (Live on the [[BBC]])\". The B-side was a then unreleased cover of [[N.W.A]]'s \"[[Fuck tha Police]]\", recorded live on August 13, 1995 at a benefit concert for [[Mumia Abu-Jamal]] at the Capitol Ballroom in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/evil-empire-mw0000647704|title=Evil Empire \u2013 Rage Against the Machine|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 15, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-04-25/features/9604250332_1_evil-empire-zack-de-la-rocha-pit-bull|title=Saved By a Guitar|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=April 25, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|url=https://ew.com/article/1996/04/19/evil-empire/|title=Evil Empire|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=April 19, 1996|accessdate=February 15, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021234948/https://ew.com/article/1996/04/19/evil-empire/|archivedate=October 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Chirazi|first=Steffan|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/article/POP-CDS-Richard-Thompson-Broods-And-Rocks-on-2986404.php|title=Rage Keeps Politics, Adds Stronger Music|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=April 14, 1996|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Cromelin|first=Richard|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-04-14/entertainment/ca-58322_1_album-review|title=Rage Against the Machine 'Evil Empire' Epic|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 14, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cigarettes|first=Johnny|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000673reviews.html|title=Rage Against the Machine \u2013 Evil Empire|journal=[[NME]]|date=April 13, 1996|accessdate=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817181817/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000673reviews.html|archivedate=August 17, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 6.1/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Schreiber|first=Ryan|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/r/rage-against-the-machine/evil-empire.shtml|title=Rage Against The Machine: Evil Empire|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=December 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816184833/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/r/rage-against-the-machine/evil-empire.shtml|archivedate=August 16, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/evil-empire-19960418|title=Evil Empire|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 18, 1996|accessdate=March 7, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gold|first=Jonathan|authorlink=Jonathan Gold|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXQ6nPE3H9wC&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103|title=Rage Against the Machine: Evil Empire|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|volume=12|issue=2|date=May 1996|accessdate=March 7, 2012|page=103}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv796-96.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|date=July 23, 1996|accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\"This music isn't supposed to be fun,\" noted ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. \"Rage Against the Machine have jacked up the [[political sociology|sociopolitical]] [[siege mentality]] in their [[Rap rock|metallic hip-hop]] to such a [[dogma]]tic degree \u2013 and honed their sound to such maniacally shrill perfection \u2013 that the band and the roaring joys of its harangue 'n' roll seem virtually [[Asexuality|sexless]].\"<ref>''[[Rolling Stone]] Yearbook'', 26 December 1996\u20139 January 1997</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track 