{"title_page": "Louis-Ren\u00e9 Levassor de Latouche Tr\u00e9ville", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{redirect|Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville||Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Louis-Ren\u00e9 Madelaine Le Vassor\n|honorific_suffix  = comte de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville\n|image=Louis-Ren\u00e9 Levassor de Latouche Tr\u00e9ville-Antoine Maurin.png\n|caption=Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, by [[Antoine Maurin]]\n|birth_date=3 June 1745\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1804|8|19|1745|6|3|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Rochefort, Charente-Maritime|Rochefort-sur-mer]], France \n|death_place=[[Toulon]], France\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Kingdom of France}}<br />{{flag|Kingdom of the French}}<br />{{flag|French First Republic}}\n|branch={{navy|Kingdom of France}}\n|serviceyears=1758 \u2014 1804\n|rank=[[Vice-admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=\n|battles=;[[Seven Years' War]]\n* [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]]\n;[[American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[Action of 7 June 1780]] {{WIA}}\n* [[Action of 21 July 1781]]\n* [[Action of 5 September 1782]]\n* [[Action of 15 September 1782]] {{POW}}\n;[[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n* [[Raids on Boulogne]]\n* [[Saint-Domingue expedition]]\n;[[Napoleonic wars]]\n|awards=Commander of the [[Legion of Honour]]<br />\nName [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the [[Arc de Triomphe]]\n|relations=Son to [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]]<br />\nNephew to [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Louis-Ren\u00e9 Madelaine Le Vassor, comte de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville'''<ref name=levot295>Levot, p.295</ref> (3 June 1745<ref name=levot295 /> \u2013 19 August 1804<ref name=levot296>Levot, p.296</ref>) was a French Vice-admiral. He fought in the [[American War of Independence]] and became a prominent figure of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and of the [[Napoleonic wars]].\n\nBorn into a noble family of naval officers, Latouche enlisted at the age of 13. He rose to become a competent frigate captain, battling several British ships during the [[American War of Independence]]. His two-frigate squadron once manoeuvred a 74-gun ship of the line to the point of sinking, and he was entrusted with important personalities of the time as passengers, notably [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] and the [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]].\n\nDuring the Revolution, Latouche, a [[Freemason]] and aide to [[Phillipe \u00c9galit\u00e9]], took progressive positions as a deputy in the [[Estates General (France)|Estates General]] and later in the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]]. His nobility nevertheless made him a target during the [[Reign of Terror]], and he was imprisoned and only freed from prison by the [[Thermidorian Reaction]].\n\nReturned to the Navy after a long period of unemployment, Latouche took command of the [[Flottille de Boulogne]], where he repelled the [[Raids on Boulogne]] organised by [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson]]. He then served in the [[Saint-Domingue expedition]], which irrevocably compromised his health. After his return, he took command of the fleet in Toulon, reorganising it into a potent tool again, but he succumbed to a relapse of illness before he had a chance to use it. Under his successor [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve|Villeneuve]], the fleet he had refurbished was crushed at the [[Battle of Trafalgar]].\n\n==Career==\nLatouche was born in [[Rochefort-sur-mer]], [[Charente-Maritime]]. His father, [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]], had been the governor of Martinique, until the [[Invasion of Martinique (1762)|Invasion of 1762]], and chief of the naval forces of Rochefort.<ref name=guerin429>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.429</ref> His uncle, [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]],<ref name=guerin426>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.426</ref> served as a Rear-Admiral, commanding the light squadron of the France-Spanish fleet under [[Louis Guillouet, comte d'Orvilliers|Orvilliers]] in 1780.<ref name=levot295 />\n\n=== Early career ===\nAt the age of 13, Latouche joined the [[Gardes de la Marine]],<ref name=levot295 /> and took part in numerous naval actions during the [[Seven Years' War]]. He started sailing on the ''Hardi'', ferrying troops to Canada in 1758,<ref>Granier, p.232</ref> and took part in his first action, in 1759 aboard the 64-gun [[French ship Dragon (1748)|''Dragon'']],<ref name=levot295 /> which was under his uncle's command,<ref name=guerin428>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.428</ref> taking part in the [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]].<ref name=levot295 /> He also served on the [[Pram (ship)|pram]] [[French ship Louise (1760)|''Louise'']] and harassed the blockading British squadron [[\u00cele-d'Aix]] in October 1760, still under his uncle.<ref name=guerin428 /> In 1762 he served on the 74-gun [[French ship Intr\u00e9pide (1747)|''Intr\u00e9pide'']] and on ''[[French ship Tonnant (1740)|Tonnant]]''. In the summer of that year, Latouche was detached to command two gunboats with which he attacked two British ships, one 60-gun and one 74-gun, waging a two-hour battle.<ref name=guerin430>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.430</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Treaty of Paris (1763)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1763, Latouche took part in training campaigns under his uncle Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville and Admiral [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing|d'Estaing]],<ref name=guerin430 /> serving on the ships ''Garonne'' in 1763, and ''Hardi'' and ''Bricole'' in 1765.\n\nIn September 1768, aged 23, he was promoted to Ensign. Perhaps under pressure from his family, who hoped for quicker promotions,<ref name=guerin430 /> or because the reform of the Navy forced him to retire,<ref name=hennequin107>Hennequin, p.107</ref> he resigned from the Navy and enlisted in the Army.<ref name=guerin430 /> He became an aide to Governor-General [[Victor-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Charpentier|d'Ennery]],<ref name=hennequin107 /> newly appointed governor of [[Martinique]], who obtained a commission as a cavalry captain for him.<ref name=hennequin107 /> In 1771, he transferred as captain to the [[R\u00e9giment de La Rochefoucauld-Dragons]], a [[dragoon]] regiment, and became [[Aide-de-camp]] to Governor General [[Louis-Florent, marquis de Vali\u00e8re|Vali\u00e8re]],<ref name=hennequin108>Hennequin, p.108</ref> who commanded at Saint-Domingue.<ref name=granier233>Granier, p.233</ref>\n\nIn 1772, Navy Minister [[Pierre \u00c9tienne Bourgeois de Boynes|Boynes]] acceded to repeated requests from Latouche's family,<ref name=hennequin108 /> and he was reinstated in the Navy as \"''capitaine de br\u00fblot''\".<ref name=levot295 /> Latouche was appointed to command the [[fluyt]] ''Courtier''.<ref name=hennequin108 /> In 1774, Latouche put forward a proposition to the Ministry Navy for an exploratory expedition to [[Circumnavigation|circumnavigate]] Australia to see whether [[New Holland (Australia)|New Holland]] and [[New South Wales]] were separated by a channel; the plan was rejected, as the Ministry preferred using [[Mauritius|\u00cele de France]] as the forward base for such an operation.<ref>Day, pp.129-130</ref> Latouche corresponded with Captain [[James Cook|Cook]] on exploration plans in 1775 and 1776.<ref>Lynn, p.272</ref>\n\n=== Service on ''Hermione'' and the American War of Independence ===\n[[File:Marins-illustres-489-b.png|thumb|left|upright|Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as represented in Gu\u00e9rin's 1845 ''Marins Illustres''.]]\nIn May 1777, he was promoted to Lieutenant and was granted the Lieutenant commander of the 20-gun [[corvette]] ''Rossignol'',<ref name=levot295 /> which escorted convoys and ferried messages.<ref name=guerin430 /> He captured two English privateers and three merchantmen.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=hennequin108 /> His prizes saw him appointed [[Order of Saint Louis|Knight of the Order of Saint-Louis]].<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin430 /> He was appointed [[commander]] of  the 26-gun frigate [[French frigate Hermione (1779)|''Hermione'']].<ref name=guerin430 />\n\nOn 28 May 1779, ''Hermione'' spotted a British privateer, which she lured into a trap by feigning fleeing in the night. In order to induce a tiring chase, Latouche let his ship's beacon be glimpsed intermittently, before doubling back to attack his opponent in the morning. The privateer was the 18-gun ''Diffidence'', of Falmouth.<ref name=guerin431>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.431</ref> The next day, another 18-gun privateer attacked and Latouche captured her too, using the same ruse.<ref name=guerin431 /><ref group=Note>Gu\u00e9rin (p.431) indicates that her name signified ''Resolution of the Ladies of London'', possibly meaning ''Ladies' Resolution'', of London.</ref>  Latouche then returned to Rochefort with his two prizes and numerous prisoners.<ref name=guerin431 />\n\nFrom 21 March to 28 April 1780,<ref name=roche241>Roche, p.241</ref> Latouche carried General [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Lafayette]] as a passenger on a transatlantic voyage from France to Boston.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin431 /> Then, joining the fleet under Rear-Admiral [[Charles Ren\u00e9 Dominique Sochet, Chevalier Destouches|Destouches]], and under orders from [[Jacques-Melchior Saint-Laurent, Comte de Barras|Barras]] and [[Charles-Henri-Louis d'Arsac de Ternay|Ternay]],<ref name=hennequin108 /> he directed the building of several artillery batteries for the defence of [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=guerin431 />\n\nAfter he had completed the batteries, Latouche received authorization to cruise off [[Long Island]] and intercept shipping to [[New York City]].<ref name=guerin431 /> He quickly captured two prizes, before spotting four sails on 7 June 1780: these were the frigate [[USS Hancock (1776)|''Iris'']] and three lesser warships.<ref name=guerin431 /> In the ensuing [[Action of 7 June 1780]], Latouche was himself shot in the arm by a musket ball,<ref name=levot295 /> and ''Hermione'' suffered ten deaths and 37 wounded.<ref>Troude, vol.2, p.80.</ref><ref group=Note>In his biography of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, Hennequin (vol.2, p.108) gives a figure of 37 killed and 53 wounded. The figure of ten killed and 37 wounded comes from a lettre of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville himself to his opponent, Captain James Hawker, quoted by Troude (vol.2, p.80).</ref> His opponent, Captain James Hawker, later accused him of fleeing the scene, to which Latouche replied \"In my poor state, I could not pursue you. Why then did you not continue the fight?\"<ref group=Note>\"''D\u00e9labr\u00e9 comme je l'\u00e9tais, je ne pouvais vous poursuivre. Pourquoi d\u00e8s lors n'avez-vous pas continu\u00e9 le combat?''\" Quoted in Levot, p.295</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville participated in the [[Battle of Cape Henry]], which took place at the mouth of [[Chesapeake Bay]].<ref>Taillemite, p.310</ref> This action has led to a commonly repeated, but erroneous, report that Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville engaged in a \"battle against the ''Chesapeake'' (March 1781)\".<ref group=Note>The error traces back to George Six's ''Dictionnaire Biographique des G\u00e9n\u00e9raux et Amiraux Fran\u00e7ais de la R\u00e9volution et de l'Empire 1792\u20131814'' (1934). This is the usual source for the misattribution. For example, see: Granier, p.233</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 1781, Latouche's father, [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]], died in Paris. Latouche inherited his title, and thereafter was styled \"Comte de Latouche\".<ref name=guerin436 />\n\n[[File:Combat naval de Louisbourg 1781.jpg|thumb|Naval battle of Louisbourg, 21 July 1781, by [[Auguste-Louis de Rossel de Cercy]].]]\nLatouche was promoted to Captain after the action of 7 June 1780. He then continued cruising off the coast of North America as part of a squadron under the command of Admiral [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Galaup, comte de Lap\u00e9rouse|Lap\u00e9rouse]], whose flagship was [[French frigate Astr\u00e9e (1780)|''Astr\u00e9e'']].<ref name=levot295 />\n\nOn 21 July, the two frigates encountered a British convoy off the coast of [[Nova Scotia|New Scotland]]. In the resulting [[naval battle of Louisbourg]], ''Astr\u00e9e'' and ''Hermione'' forced [[USS Boston (1777)|HMS ''Charlestown'']] to strike her colours, but failed to board her, allowing her to flee during the night.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin433>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.433</ref> They did however capture the 14-gun escort, ''Jack'', and three merchantmen, which they brought to Boston.<ref name=guerin433 />\n\n=== Service on ''Aigle'' ===\nAfter returning to France, Latouche was promoted to Captain on 20 June 1781.<ref name=guerin433 /> In 1782, he was tasked with ferrying officials, large sums of money<ref name=hennequin109>Hennequin, p.109</ref><ref group=Note>Hennequin (p.109) gives a figure of \"three millions in gold\", without specifying the currency unit; probably [[French livre]]s. Three million livres amounted to the worth of six [[74-gun]] ships of the line, for instance.</ref> and equipment to America, leading a two-frigate squadron comprising [[French frigate Aigle (1782)|''Aigle'']] and [[French frigate Gloire (1778)|''Gloire'']], under Captain de Vallongue.<ref name=guerin433 />\n\nLatouche assumed command of the frigate [[French frigate Aigle (1782)|''Aigle'']]<ref name=\"levot296\" /> which, along with the ''Gloire'', ferried funds and equipment for the fleet of Admiral de [[Louis-Philippe de Vaudreuil|Vaudreuil]].<ref name=guerin433 />  On 5 September 1782, the squadron encountered the lone 74-gun [[French ship Hector (1756)|HMS ''Hector'']]: in the [[Action of 5 September 1782|ensuing two-day battle]], the two frigates heavily damaged the ''Hector'', and only failed to captured her when a British squadron appeared on the horizon. Latouche retreated, and ''Hector'' foundered a few days later.<ref name=guerin433 /><ref name=hennequin109 />\n\n===Capture===\n{{further|Action of 15 September 1782}}\nThe frigates continued on their journey when, on 12 September, they spotted a British squadron, comprising two ships of the line with a frigate, two corvettes and a [[brig-sloop]]. Latouche captured the brig, {{HMS|Racoon|1780|6}}.<ref name=guerin435>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.435</ref> Latouche then tacked into the [[Delaware River]], as {{HMS|Vestal|1779|6}}, {{HMS|Bonetta|1779|6}}, and the prize ''Sophie'', led by Captain G.K. Elphinston in {{HMS|Warwick|1767|2}}, gave chase. Latouche landed his passengers and treasure with launches from the frigates.<ref name=guerin435 /> He then attempted to escape his much stronger opponents by sailing over the banks at the mouth of the Delaware River, but ''Aigle'' ran aground; ''Gloire'' also touched bottom, but she managed to free herself and reach the channel.<ref name=guerin435 /> Latouche attempted to free ''Aigle'', but with the retreating tide, she became not only more and more firmly beached, but also fell on her side, rendering her battery unserviceable.<ref name=guerin435 /> Seeing his ship lost, Latouche had her the masts chopped off and her hull pierced; he then evacuated her crew;<ref name=guerin435 /> staying behind with only a few men, Latouche fired a few shots from his [[stern chaser]]s before striking his colours.<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=guerin435 /><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12388|pages=3\u20134|date=12 November 1782}}</ref> Despite the measures to disable ''Aigle'', the British were able to recover her and took her into service as HMS ''Aigle''.\n\nAdmiral Vaudreuil wrote to the Minister of the Navy [[Charles Eug\u00e8ne Gabriel de La Croix|Castrie]]:\n{{cquote|Mister de la Touche deserves your reprimand; he had on board with him a kept woman with whom he lived; the English, having captured her, have returned her to him as though she was his wife. This is known and cannot but make a bad impression in a country with good morals.<ref name=granier234>Granier, p.234</ref><ref group=Note>\"''Monsieur de La Touche m\u00e9rite que vous lui fassiez une r\u00e9primande; il avait dans un b\u00e2timent \u00e0 sa suite, une cr\u00e9ature avec laquelle il vit; les Anglais l'ayant prise la lui ont renvoy\u00e9e comme sa femme. Cela s'est su et ne peut faire qu'un mauvais effet dans un pays aux bonnes m\u0153urs.''\"</ref>}}\n\nLatouche was taken as a prisoner to New York, and transferred from there to England.<ref name=guerin436>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.436</ref> He remained a prisoner until the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1783.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n=== Service in France during the Revolution ===\nUpon Latouche's return in France, he was appointed to direct Rochefort harbour.<ref name=guerin436 /> He was also tasked with drawing a map of [[Ol\u00e9ron]],<ref name=guerin436 /> which was published in the first volume of ''Hydrographie fran\u00e7aise''.<ref name=guerin436 /><ref name=hennequin110>Hennequin, p.110</ref><ref group=Note>Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was not, however, the author of two treatises, one on [[political economy]] and the other on [[agriculture]]; the author of those works was probably [[Jacques Antoine Creuz\u00e9-Latouche]]. See Levot, p.298.</ref> In 1784 he succeeded [[Bruni d'Entrecasteaux]] as vice-director of the Harbours and Arsenals, holding the position until 1787, when he became Chancellor to the [[Louis Philippe II, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]].<ref name=guerin436 /> Meanwhile, he had also served as an inspector for the gunnery school of the Naval Academy,<ref name=guerin436 /> and co-authored the Naval Code for 1786.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=hennequin110 /> In July 1786, he sailed a corvette from [[Honfleur]] to [[Le Havre]], ferrying king [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]].<ref name=guerin436 />\n\nHis uncle, [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]], died in 1788 and bequeathed him his name; henceforth, Latouche added \"Tr\u00e9ville\" to his name, becoming the \"comte de Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville\".<ref name=guerin436 />\n\n[[File:Scanlatouchetreville.jpg|thumb|Letter by Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville]]\nAt the beginning of the [[French Revolution]] in 1789, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was elected deputy of the [[Estates General (France)|Nobility]]<ref name=levot296 /> for the [[bailiwick]] of [[Montargis]]; he went on to sit at the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]] and held this position until it adjourned on 10 October 1791.<ref name=guerin436 /> Latouche took a liberal posture and was among the first nobles to join forces with the Third Estate.<ref name=levot296 /> In September 1791, after king Louis XVI approved the new constitution, the National Constituent Assembly disbanded, and Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville resumed his naval activities.\n\n[[File:Rouget - Louis-Ren\u00e9-Madeleine Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville, contre-amiral en 1792 (1745-1804).jpg|left|upright|thumb|Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as a Rear-Admiral, in 1792. [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis-Philippe]] commissioned the painting for the History Museum of Versailles in 1835;[[Georges Rouget]] painted it in 1840.]]\n\nLatouche had held the rank of Rear-Admiral since 20 December 1790 reform of the navy.<ref name=guerin436 /> In this capacity, in 1792 he took command of a four-ship squadron in [[Brest, France|Brest]].<ref name=levot296 /> He sailed from Brest to [[Toulon]], on his flagship the [[French ship Languedoc (1766)|''Languedoc'']], to attach his division to the Mediterranean squadron under Rear-admiral [[Laurent Jean Fran\u00e7ois Truguet|Truguet]].<ref name=levot296 /> He took part in raids against [[Oneglia]], [[Cagliari]] and [[Nice]]<ref name=hennequin110 /> during the [[French Revolutionary Wars: Campaigns of 1796#Italy|Army of Italy]], and joined in the attack on [[Sardinia]] in October 1792 (which turned out to be a failure when the expeditionary corps was repulsed). Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville and Truguet then returned to Toulon.\n\n[[File:Moniteur-Latouche-Naples.png|thumb|upright|''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]'' relates Latouche's mission to Naples.]]\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville was promoted to Rear-Admiral on 1 January 1793.<ref name=levot296 /> He was then sent on a mission to [[Napoli]], after that kingdom's ambassador to [[Constantinople]] had precipitated a diplomatic conflict by insulting his French counterpart. Latouche threatened to bombard the city, and obtained apologies from [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies]].<ref name=granier235>Granier, p.235</ref> Latouche then departed, but had to double back to Napoli to repair due to gale-force winds, eventually making his rendezvous with Truguet on 8 February 1793.<ref name=granier235 /> On 14 February, they landed 6,000 volunteers at Cagliari, who had to reembark under fire and in a gale two days later.<ref name=granier235 /> The fleet then returned to Toulon once more.<ref name=granier235 />\n\nIn March 1793, amid the [[War of the First Coalition]], Latouche took command of the \"Naval Army of the Ocean\" (the Brest fleet), but as soon as he took up his position, revolutionary subordinates denounced him as an aristocrat. On 15 September,<ref name=guerin437>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.437</ref> at the height of the [[Reign of Terror]], he was arrested as a \"suspect\" on orders of the [[Committee of Public Safety]],<ref name=guerin437 /> and cashiered on 3 October.<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=\"guerin458\">Gu\u00e9rin, ''Histoire maritime de France'', p.458</ref> He spent one year in [[La Force Prison]],<ref name=guerin437 /> and was freed only on 20 September 1794,<ref name=guerin437 /> after the [[Thermidorian Reaction]].\n\nFreed, Latouche returned to Montargis, where he was appointed chief of the Legion of the [[National Guard (France)|National Guard]] for the district.<ref name=guerin437 /> A [[Freemasonry|Freemason]], he rose to ''V\u00e9n\u00e9rable'' in the Lodge ''Les Disciples d\u2019Heredom et de la Madeleine R\u00e9unis'', of Montargis.<ref>{{Cite book|first=Jean-Marc|last=Van Hille|title=Dictionnaire des marins francs-ma\u00e7ons, Gens de mer et professions connexes aux XVIIIe, XIXe et XXe si\u00e8cles|publisher=L'Harmattan|year=2011|page=305}}</ref> Latouche was rehabilitated under the [[French Directory|Directoire]] and had his rank reinstated in December 1795,<ref name=levot296 /> but nonetheless was left for five years without a command in the Navy.<ref name=levot296 /> From 1797 to 1798, he managed equipment for the Navy with a ship-owner friend, and by 1799 he had grown so desperate that he advertised in ''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]'' for privateer captainships.<ref>Granier, p.236</ref> It was not until 1799 that he returned to active duty.<ref name=guerin437 />\n\n=== Service at the Flottille de Boulogne ===\nIn 1799, Latouche was appointed to lead a naval division in Brest, with his mark on the 74-gun [[French ship Mont-Blanc (1791)|''Mont-Blanc'']].<ref name=guerin437 /> Soon after, he was appointed to command the full Brest fleet,<ref name=guerin437 /> and transferred his flag onto the 110-gun [[French ship Terrible (1779)|''Terrible'']].<ref name=guerin437 /> Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville defended the harbour until the government decided to disband the naval Army of Brest; Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville then sailed four of its ships to Rochefort.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n[[File:Boulogne.jpg|thumb|Nelson fails against the flotilla of Latouche Tr\u00e9ville near Boulogne, 15 August 1801]]\nSoon after, advised by Navy minister [[Pierre-Alexandre-Laurent Forfait|Forfait]],<ref name=levot296 /> [[French Consulate|First Consul]] [[Napoleon I of France|Bonaparte]] chose Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville to organise and lead the ''[[Flottille de Boulogne]]''. This vast fleet of small ships was ostensibly designed to ferry an invasion army to England,<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=guerin437 /> but was in fact a disinformation ploy to pressure the British into negotiating the [[Treaty of Amiens]].<ref>Farr\u00e8re, p.298</ref> The ploy helped to disguise the true goal of the French military, which was massing armies in Boulogne for an invasion of Austria.<ref>Granier, p.244</ref> Soon after his arrival, on 4 August and 15 August 1801, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville repelled the [[Raid on Boulogne (1801)|several British raids]] that Admiral [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson]] launched to destroy the ''Flottille''.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n=== Service at Saint-Domingue ===\nDuring the [[Peace of Amiens]], Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was appointed to command the naval squadron of Rochefort,<ref name=hennequin111>Hennequin, p.111</ref> comprising six ships of the line, six frigates and two corvettes,<ref name=guerin437 />  in the fleet of Admiral [[Villaret de Joyeuse]],<ref name=levot296 /> ferrying 3,000 men of the Army of Rhine for the [[Saint-Domingue expedition]].<ref name=guerin437 /> Latouche fought his way into the harbour of [[Port-au-Prince]], captured its forts and landed the troops.<ref name=guerin437 /> He and General Boudet captured [[Port-au-Prince]] and [[L\u00e9og\u00e2ne]]. Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville managed to obtain the peaceful surrender of General Laplume, while, in the south, General [[Charles Leclerc (general, born 1772)|Leclerc]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} forced [[Toussaint L'Ouverture]] and Christophe to submit to French authority.<ref name=granier246>Granier, p.246</ref>\n\nWith [[Villaret de Joyeuse]]'s departure in April 1802, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville stayed in Saint-Domingue with four ships of the line, nine frigates and five corvettes.<ref name=granier246 /> After the restoration of slavery on 20 May 1802, a new rebellion broke out, which overwhelmed the yellow-fever-stricken army of General Leclerc. Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville defended the harbours in the south, appointing [[Jean-Baptiste Philibert Willaumez|Willaumez]] to the western naval station of Saint-Domingue.<ref name=granier246 /> The situation grew even more desperate after the British started the [[War of the Third Coalition]] in May 1803: Willaumez had to return to France to repair his frigate, damaged in the [[Action of 28 June 1803]], and the British effected a [[Blockade of Saint-Domingue]] that ended with the complete destruction of Rochambeau's army.<ref name=granier246 /> In October 1803, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville obtained free passage from the British due to his poor health, and returned to France.<ref name=hennequin111 /><ref name=granier246 />\n\n=== Service as commander of the fleet of Toulon ===\n\n[[File:Rouget - Louis-Ren\u00e9-Madeleine Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville, vice-amiral en 1803 (1745-1804).jpg|right|upright|thumb|Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as a Vice-Admiral, in 1803. [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis-Philippe]] commissioned the painting for the History Museum of Versailles in 1835; [[Georges Rouget]] painted it in 1840.]]\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville was made a vice-Admiral in December 1803. Returned to France, he was appointed general inspector of the coasts of the Mediterranean, before taking command of the fleet of Toulon,<ref name=hennequin111 /> with his flag on the brand-new 80-gun ''[[French ship Bucentaure (1804)|Bucentaure]]''.<ref name=guerin438>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.438</ref> At the time, the squadron counted only seven ships of the line and four frigates, and discipline was much weakened;<ref name=hennequin111 /> in particular, Navy officers slept aboard their ships only when forced to do so by their duty.<ref name=hennequin111 /> Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville made a point to live on his ship, and morale quickly improved under his example and leadership.<ref name=hennequin111 />\n\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville decided to have one ship or frigate patrol for three days outside the harbour, in rotation, while another would always be ready to put to sail at the first signal.<ref name=hennequin112>Hennequin, p.112</ref> Furthermore, the entire squadron regularly scrambled to support the cruisers whenever superior British forces ventured into Toulon harbour, preventing the British from conducting useful reconnaissance of French activities in the area.<ref name=hennequin112 /> Over the time, the squadron received three more ships of the line and three more frigates as reinforcements.<ref name=hennequin112 />\n\nIn late June 1804, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville suffered a relapse of a medical condition contracted at Saint-Domingue.<ref group=Note>Hennequin (''Biographie maritime'', vol.2, p.112), Levot (''Gloires maritimes de la France'', p.297), Gu\u00e9rin (''Marins illustres'', p.629) and Taillemite (''Dictionnaire des marins fran\u00e7ais'', p.310) are all vague as to what exact medical condition is involved. Hennequin is the most precise on this question, stating that \"around the last days of July, the symptoms of the disease that had required his return from Saint-Domingue to Europe became very obvious, and soon took an alarming turn.\" (\"''Vers les derniers jours du mois de juillet, les sympt\u00f4mes de la maladie qui avait n\u00e9cessit\u00e9 son retour de Saint-Domingue en Europe se d\u00e9clar\u00e8rent vivement, et bient\u00f4t elle prit un caract\u00e8re alarment.''\"). Levot states that Latouche \"succumbed on ''Bucentaure'' to the consequences of the disease he had contracted at Saint-Domingue\" (\"''Le 19 ao\u00fbt 1804, il succombait sur le ''Bucentaure'' aux suites de la maladie qu'il avait contract\u00e9e \u00e0 Saint-Domingue''\").</ref> However, he constantly refused to transfer ashore, stating \"An admiral is only too glad when he can die under the flag of his ship.\"<ref group=Note>\"Un amiral est trop heureux lorsqu'il peut mourir sous le pavillon de son vaisesau.\" Quote in Hennequin, p.112</ref><ref name=hennequin112 /> Indeed, after a 10-day struggle, on 19 August, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville  died aboard ''Bucentaure''.<ref name=hennequin112 /> Lord Nelson later wrote:\n{{cquote|The French papers say he died of walking so often up to the signal-post to watch us: I always pronounced that would be his death.<ref>Bradford, last page of chapter 32.</ref>}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville  was buried in Toulon graveyard. In 1810, a seven-metre-high pyramidal mausoleum was built at the S\u00e9maphore de la Croix des Signaux, at Cape C\u00e9pet, from where Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville had observed the British in his last year.<ref>Granier, p.248</ref> On 14 October 1902, military authorities decided to move the mausoleum<ref group=Note>Allegedly, because they saw the mausoleum as a potential [[daymark]] for an enemy fleet. Emmanuel Davin, ''Les amis du vieux Toulon''; quoted in Granier, p.249.</ref> to the military graveyard of [[Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer]]; the body was transferred on  29 April 1903.<ref>[http://www.ville-saintmandrier.fr/office/tourisme/cimetiere.html ville-saintmandrier.fr] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416135821/http://www.ville-saintmandrier.fr/office/tourisme/cimetiere.html |date=16 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFrench authors and historians often compared Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville to Nelson, partly because he fought and defeated him in the [[Raids on Boulogne]], partly because, had it not been for his untimely death, he would have opposed Nelson at [[Trafalgar Campaign|Trafalgar]].<ref>R\u00e9mi Monaque, ''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, 1745\u20131804 : l'amiral qui d\u00e9fiait Nelson'', \u00e9ditions SPM, 2000, {{ISBN|2-901952-36-4}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Arc de Triomphe mg 6823.jpg|right|upright|thumb|LATOUCHE [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the [[Arc de Triomphe]] (left column, 10th from top).]]\nThe name ''Latouche'' was [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the north face of the [[Arc de Triomphe]] in his honour.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Notice historique sur l'Arc de Triomphe et l'\u00c9toile |last= Thierry |first=J. |author2=Coulon, G.  |year=1838 |publisher=Rosselin |location=Paris |language=French |page=24 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNxSAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA24 |accessdate=6 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThree ships of the [[French Navy]] have been named [[French ship Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in his honour: the steam aviso [[French aviso Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (1860)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in 1860; the armoured cruiser [[French cruiser Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in 1892; and the [[Georges Leygues-class frigate|F70-type]] destroyer [[French frigate Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (D646)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']], presently in commission.\n{{Gallery\n|title=Ships of the French Navy named ''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville''\n|width=200\n|height=\n|lines=2\n|align=center\n|File:Le RenardWiki.jpg|The steam 2nd-class aviso ''Renard'', similar to [[French aviso Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] (1860-1886)\n|File:Latouche-Treville far134.jpg|The armoured cruiser [[French cruiser Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']]\n|File:FS Latouche Treville (D 646).jpg|The [[Georges Leygues-class frigate|F70-type]] destroyer [[French frigate Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (D646)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']]\n}}\n\n== Notes, citations and references ==\n{{Portal|France|Biography|American Revolutionary War|United States|North America}}\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== References ===\n* {{cite book|title=Nelson: The Essential Hero|first=Ernle|last=Bradford|authorlink=Ernle Bradford|publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited|year=1977|isbn=0-333-18561-7}}\n* {{cite book|title=The A to Z of the Discovery and Exploration of Australia\n|first=Alan|last=Day|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0810868106}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la Marine fran\u00e7aise|first=Claude|last=Farr\u00e8re|authorlink=Claude Farr\u00e8re|publisher=Flammarion|year=1956|place=Paris|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Les marins illustres de la France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1845|publisher=Belin-Leprieur et Morizot|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uutuoMfBe4AC|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire maritime de France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1857|publisher=Dufour et Mulat|url=https://books.google.com/?id=95BKAAAAMAAJ|language=French|volume=5}}\n* {{cite book|title=Biographie maritime ou notices historiques sur la vie et les campagnes des marins c\u00e9l\u00e8bres fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers|last=Hennequin|first=Joseph Fran\u00e7ois Gabriel|year=1835|publisher=Regnault \u00e9diteur|location=Paris|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YbdCAAAAYAAJ|language=French|volume=2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Les gloires maritimes de la France: notices biographiques sur les plus c\u00e9l\u00e8bres marins|last=Levot|first=Prosper|authorlink=Prosper Levot|year=1866|publisher=Bertrand|url=https://books.google.com/?id=08O_XGLO43QC|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Captain Cook, Master of the Seas|first=Frank M.|last=Lynn|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0300184310|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ridlr1YNgXwC}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=1}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=2}}\n* {{cite book|first=\u00c9tienne|last=Taillemite|year=2002|title=Dictionnaire des Marins fran\u00e7ais|isbn=2-84734-008-4|publisher=Tallandier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Latouche Treville}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1804 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Rochefort, Charente-Maritime]]\n[[Category:French Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:French naval commanders of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n[[Category:French Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe]]\n[[Category:People of the Haitian Revolution]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{redirect|Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville||Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Louis-Ren\u00e9 Madelaine Le Vassor\n|honorific_suffix  = comte de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville\n|image=Louis-Ren\u00e9 Levassor de Latouche Tr\u00e9ville-Antoine Maurin.png\n|caption=Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, by [[Antoine Maurin]]\n|birth_date=3 June 1745\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1804|8|19|1745|6|3|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Rochefort, Charente-Maritime|Rochefort-sur-mer]], France \n|death_place=[[Toulon]], France\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Kingdom of France}}<br />{{flag|Kingdom of the French}}<br />{{flag|French First Republic}}\n|branch={{navy|Kingdom of France}}\n|serviceyears=1758 \u2014 1804\n|rank=[[Vice-admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=\n|battles=;[[Seven Years' War]]\n* [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]]\n;[[American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[Action of 7 June 1780]] {{WIA}}\n* [[Action of 21 July 1781]]\n* [[Action of 5 September 1782]]\n* [[Action of 15 September 1782]] {{POW}}\n;[[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n* [[Raids on Boulogne]]\n* [[Saint-Domingue expedition]]\n;[[Napoleonic wars]]\n|awards=Commander of the [[Legion of Honour]]<br />\nName [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the [[Arc de Triomphe]]\n|relations=Son to [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]]<br />\nNephew to [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Louis-Ren\u00e9 Madelaine Le Vassor, comte de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville'''<ref name=levot295>Levot, p.295</ref> (3 June 1745<ref name=levot295 /> \u2013 19 August 1804<ref name=levot296>Levot, p.296</ref>) was a French Vice-admiral. He fought in the [[American War of Independence]] and became a prominent figure of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and of the [[Napoleonic wars]].\n\nBorn into a noble family of naval officers, Latouche enlisted at the age of 13. He rose to become a competent frigate captain, battling several British ships during the [[American War of Independence]]. His two-frigate squadron once manoeuvred a 74-gun ship of the line to the point of sinking, and he was entrusted with important personalities of the time as passengers, notably [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] and the [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]].\n\nDuring the Revolution, Latouche, a [[Freemason]] and aide to [[Phillipe \u00c9galit\u00e9]], took progressive positions as a deputy in the [[Estates General (France)|Estates General]] and later in the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]]. His nobility nevertheless made him a target during the [[Reign of Terror]], and he was imprisoned and only freed from prison by the [[Thermidorian Reaction]].\n\nReturned to the Navy after a long period of unemployment, Latouche took command of the [[Flottille de Boulogne]], where he repelled the [[Raids on Boulogne]] organised by [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson]]. He then served in the [[Saint-Domingue expedition]], which irrevocably compromised his health. After his return, he took command of the fleet in Toulon, reorganising it into a potent tool again, but he succumbed to a relapse of illness before he had a chance to use it. Under his successor [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve|Villeneuve]], the fleet he had refurbished was crushed at the [[Battle of Trafalgar]].\n\n==Career==\nLatouche was born in [[Rochefort-sur-mer]], [[Charente-Maritime]]. His father, [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]], had been the governor of Martinique, until the [[Invasion of Martinique (1762)|Invasion of 1762]], and chief of the naval forces of Rochefort.<ref name=guerin429>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.429</ref> His uncle, [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]],<ref name=guerin426>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.426</ref> served as a Rear-Admiral, commanding the light squadron of the France-Spanish fleet under [[Louis Guillouet, comte d'Orvilliers|Orvilliers]] in 1780.<ref name=levot295 />\n\n=== Early career ===\nAt the age of 13, Latouche joined the [[Gardes de la Marine]],<ref name=levot295 /> and took part in numerous naval actions during the [[Seven Years' War]]. He started sailing on the ''Hardi'', ferrying troops to Canada in 1758,<ref>Granier, p.232</ref> and took part in his first action, in 1759 aboard the 64-gun [[French ship Dragon (1748)|''Dragon'']],<ref name=levot295 /> which was under his uncle's command,<ref name=guerin428>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.428</ref> taking part in the [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]].<ref name=levot295 /> He also served on the [[Pram (ship)|pram]] [[French ship Louise (1760)|''Louise'']] and harassed the blockading British squadron [[\u00cele-d'Aix]] in October 1760, still under his uncle.<ref name=guerin428 /> In 1762 he served on the 74-gun [[French ship Intr\u00e9pide (1747)|''Intr\u00e9pide'']] and on ''[[French ship Tonnant (1740)|Tonnant]]''. In the summer of that year, Latouche was detached to command two gunboats with which he attacked two British ships, one 60-gun and one 74-gun, waging a two-hour battle.<ref name=guerin430>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.430</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Treaty of Paris (1763)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1763, Latouche took part in training campaigns under his uncle Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville and Admiral [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing|d'Estaing]],<ref name=guerin430 /> serving on the ships ''Garonne'' in 1763, and ''Hardi'' and ''Bricole'' in 1765.\n\nIn September 1768, aged 23, he was promoted to Ensign. Perhaps under pressure from his family, who hoped for quicker promotions,<ref name=guerin430 /> or because the reform of the Navy forced him to retire,<ref name=hennequin107>Hennequin, p.107</ref> he resigned from the Navy and enlisted in the Army.<ref name=guerin430 /> He became an aide to Governor-General [[Victor-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Charpentier|d'Ennery]],<ref name=hennequin107 /> newly appointed governor of [[Martinique]], who obtained a commission as a cavalry captain for him.<ref name=hennequin107 /> In 1771, he transferred as captain to the [[R\u00e9giment de La Rochefoucauld-Dragons]], a [[dragoon]] regiment, and became [[Aide-de-camp]] to Governor General [[Louis-Florent, marquis de Vali\u00e8re|Vali\u00e8re]],<ref name=hennequin108>Hennequin, p.108</ref> who commanded at Saint-Domingue.<ref name=granier233>Granier, p.233</ref>\n\nIn 1772, Navy Minister [[Pierre \u00c9tienne Bourgeois de Boynes|Boynes]] acceded to repeated requests from Latouche's family,<ref name=hennequin108 /> and he was reinstated in the Navy as \"''capitaine de br\u00fblot''\".<ref name=levot295 /> Latouche was appointed to command the [[fluyt]] ''Courtier''.<ref name=hennequin108 /> In 1774, Latouche put forward a proposition to the Ministry Navy for an exploratory expedition to [[Circumnavigation|circumnavigate]] Australia to see whether [[New Holland (Australia)|New Holland]] and [[New South Wales]] were separated by a channel; the plan was rejected, as the Ministry preferred using [[Mauritius|\u00cele de France]] as the forward base for such an operation.<ref>Day, pp.129-130</ref> Latouche corresponded with Captain [[James Cook|Cook]] on exploration plans in 1775 and 1776.<ref>Lynn, p.272</ref>\n\n=== Service on ''Hermione'' and the American War of Independence ===\n[[File:Marins-illustres-489-b.png|thumb|left|upright|Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as represented in Gu\u00e9rin's 1845 ''Marins Illustres''.]]\nIn May 1777, he was promoted to Lieutenant and was granted the Lieutenant commander of the 20-gun [[corvette]] ''Rossignol'',<ref name=levot295 /> which escorted convoys and ferried messages.<ref name=guerin430 /> He captured two English privateers and three merchantmen.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=hennequin108 /> His prizes saw him appointed [[Order of Saint Louis|Knight of the Order of Saint-Louis]].<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin430 /> He was appointed [[commander]] of  the 26-gun frigate [[French frigate Hermione (1779)|''Hermione'']].<ref name=guerin430 />\n\nOn 28 May 1779, ''Hermione'' spotted a British privateer, which she lured into a trap by feigning fleeing in the night. In order to induce a tiring chase, Latouche let his ship's beacon be glimpsed intermittently, before doubling back to attack his opponent in the morning. The privateer was the 18-gun ''Diffidence'', of Falmouth.<ref name=guerin431>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.431</ref> The next day, another 18-gun privateer attacked and Latouche captured her too, using the same ruse.<ref name=guerin431 /><ref group=Note>Gu\u00e9rin (p.431) indicates that her name signified ''Resolution of the Ladies of London'', possibly meaning ''Ladies' Resolution'', of London.</ref>  Latouche then returned to Rochefort with his two prizes and numerous prisoners.<ref name=guerin431 />\n\nFrom 21 March to 28 April 1780,<ref name=roche241>Roche, p.241</ref> Latouche carried General [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Lafayette]] as a passenger on a transatlantic voyage from France to Boston.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin431 /> Then, joining the fleet under Rear-Admiral [[Charles Ren\u00e9 Dominique Sochet, Chevalier Destouches|Destouches]], and under orders from [[Jacques-Melchior Saint-Laurent, Comte de Barras|Barras]] and [[Charles-Henri-Louis d'Arsac de Ternay|Ternay]],<ref name=hennequin108 /> he directed the building of several artillery batteries for the defence of [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=guerin431 />\n\nAfter he had completed the batteries, Latouche received authorization to cruise off [[Long Island]] and intercept shipping to [[New York City]].<ref name=guerin431 /> He quickly captured two prizes, before spotting four sails on 7 June 1780: these were the frigate [[USS Hancock (1776)|''Iris'']] and three lesser warships.<ref name=guerin431 /> In the ensuing [[Action of 7 June 1780]], Latouche was himself shot in the arm by a musket ball,<ref name=levot295 /> and ''Hermione'' suffered ten deaths and 37 wounded.<ref>Troude, vol.2, p.80.</ref><ref group=Note>In his biography of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, Hennequin (vol.2, p.108) gives a figure of 37 killed and 53 wounded. The figure of ten killed and 37 wounded comes from a lettre of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville himself to his opponent, Captain James Hawker, quoted by Troude (vol.2, p.80).</ref> His opponent, Captain James Hawker, later accused him of fleeing the scene, to which Latouche replied \"In my poor state, I could not pursue you. Why then did you not continue the fight?\"<ref group=Note>\"''D\u00e9labr\u00e9 comme je l'\u00e9tais, je ne pouvais vous poursuivre. Pourquoi d\u00e8s lors n'avez-vous pas continu\u00e9 le combat?''\" Quoted in Levot, p.295</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville participated in the [[Battle of Cape Henry]], which took place at the mouth of [[Chesapeake Bay]].<ref>Taillemite, p.310</ref> This action has led to a commonly repeated, but erroneous, report that Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville engaged in a \"battle against the ''Chesapeake'' (March 1781)\".<ref group=Note>The error traces back to George Six's ''Dictionnaire Biographique des G\u00e9n\u00e9raux et Amiraux Fran\u00e7ais de la R\u00e9volution et de l'Empire 1792\u20131814'' (1934). This is the usual source for the misattribution. For example, see: Granier, p.233</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 1781, Latouche's father, [[Louis-Charles Le Vassor de La Touche]], died in Paris. Latouche inherited his title, and thereafter was styled \"Comte de Latouche\".<ref name=guerin436 />\n\n[[File:Combat naval de Louisbourg 1781.jpg|thumb|Naval battle of Louisbourg, 21 July 1781, by [[Auguste-Louis de Rossel de Cercy]].]]\nLatouche was promoted to Captain after the action of 7 June 1780. He then continued cruising off the coast of North America as part of a squadron under the command of Admiral [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Galaup, comte de Lap\u00e9rouse|Lap\u00e9rouse]], whose flagship was [[French frigate Astr\u00e9e (1780)|''Astr\u00e9e'']].<ref name=levot295 />\n\nOn 21 July, the two frigates encountered a British convoy off the coast of [[Nova Scotia|New Scotland]]. In the resulting [[naval battle of Louisbourg]], ''Astr\u00e9e'' and ''Hermione'' forced [[USS Boston (1777)|HMS ''Charlestown'']] to strike her colours, but failed to board her, allowing her to flee during the night.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=guerin433>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.433</ref> They did however capture the 14-gun escort, ''Jack'', and three merchantmen, which they brought to Boston.<ref name=guerin433 />\n\n=== Service on ''Aigle'' ===\nAfter returning to France, Latouche was promoted to Captain on 20 June 1781.<ref name=guerin433 /> In 1782, he was tasked with ferrying officials, large sums of money<ref name=hennequin109>Hennequin, p.109</ref><ref group=Note>Hennequin (p.109) gives a figure of \"three millions in gold\", without specifying the currency unit; probably [[French livre]]s. Three million livres amounted to the worth of six [[74-gun]] ships of the line, for instance.</ref> and equipment to America, leading a two-frigate squadron comprising [[French frigate Aigle (1782)|''Aigle'']] and [[French frigate Gloire (1778)|''Gloire'']], under Captain de Vallongue.<ref name=guerin433 />\n\nLatouche assumed command of the frigate [[French frigate Aigle (1782)|''Aigle'']]<ref name=\"levot296\" /> which, along with the ''Gloire'', ferried funds and equipment for the fleet of Admiral de [[Louis-Philippe de Vaudreuil|Vaudreuil]].<ref name=guerin433 />  On 5 September 1782, the squadron encountered the lone 74-gun [[French ship Hector (1756)|HMS ''Hector'']]: in the [[Action of 5 September 1782|ensuing two-day battle]], the two frigates heavily damaged the ''Hector'', and only failed to captured her when a British squadron appeared on the horizon. Latouche retreated, and ''Hector'' foundered a few days later.<ref name=guerin433 /><ref name=hennequin109 />\n\n===Capture===\n{{further|Action of 15 September 1782}}\nThe frigates continued on their journey when, on 12 September, they spotted a British squadron, comprising two ships of the line with a frigate, two corvettes and a [[brig-sloop]]. Latouche captured the brig, {{HMS|Racoon|1780|6}}.<ref name=guerin435>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.435</ref> Latouche then tacked into the [[Delaware River]], as {{HMS|Vestal|1779|6}}, {{HMS|Bonetta|1779|6}}, and the prize ''Sophie'', led by Captain G.K. Elphinston in {{HMS|Warwick|1767|2}}, gave chase. Latouche landed his passengers and treasure with launches from the frigates.<ref name=guerin435 /> He then attempted to escape his much stronger opponents by sailing over the banks at the mouth of the Delaware River, but ''Aigle'' ran aground; ''Gloire'' also touched bottom, but she managed to free herself and reach the channel.<ref name=guerin435 /> Latouche attempted to free ''Aigle'', but with the retreating tide, she became not only more and more firmly beached, but also fell on her side, rendering her battery unserviceable.<ref name=guerin435 /> Seeing his ship lost, Latouche had her the masts chopped off and her hull pierced; he then evacuated her crew;<ref name=guerin435 /> staying behind with only a few men, Latouche fired a few shots from his [[stern chaser]]s before striking his colours.<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=guerin435 /><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12388|pages=3\u20134|date=12 November 1782}}</ref> Despite the measures to disable ''Aigle'', the British were able to recover her and took her into service as HMS ''Aigle''.\n\nAdmiral Vaudreuil wrote to the Minister of the Navy [[Charles Eug\u00e8ne Gabriel de La Croix|de Castrie]]:\n{{cquote|Mister de la Touche deserves your reprimand; he had on board with him a kept woman with whom he lived; the English, having captured her, have returned her to him as though she was his wife. This is known and cannot but make a bad impression in a country with good morals.<ref name=granier234>Granier, p.234</ref><ref group=Note>\"''Monsieur de La Touche m\u00e9rite que vous lui fassiez une r\u00e9primande; il avait dans un b\u00e2timent \u00e0 sa suite, une cr\u00e9ature avec laquelle il vit; les Anglais l'ayant prise la lui ont renvoy\u00e9e comme sa femme. Cela s'est su et ne peut faire qu'un mauvais effet dans un pays aux bonnes m\u0153urs.''\"</ref>}}\n\nLatouche was taken as a prisoner to New York, and transferred from there to England.<ref name=guerin436>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.436</ref> He remained a prisoner until the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1783.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n=== Service in France during the Revolution ===\nUpon Latouche's return in France, he was appointed to direct Rochefort harbour.<ref name=guerin436 /> He was also tasked with drawing a map of [[Ol\u00e9ron]],<ref name=guerin436 /> which was published in the first volume of ''Hydrographie fran\u00e7aise''.<ref name=guerin436 /><ref name=hennequin110>Hennequin, p.110</ref><ref group=Note>Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was not, however, the author of two treatises, one on [[political economy]] and the other on [[agriculture]]; the author of those works was probably [[Jacques Antoine Creuz\u00e9-Latouche]]. See Levot, p.298.</ref> In 1784 he succeeded [[Bruni d'Entrecasteaux]] as vice-director of the Harbours and Arsenals, holding the position until 1787, when he became Chancellor to the [[Louis Philippe II, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]].<ref name=guerin436 /> Meanwhile, he had also served as an inspector for the gunnery school of the Naval Academy,<ref name=guerin436 /> and co-authored the Naval Code for 1786.<ref name=levot295 /><ref name=hennequin110 /> In July 1786, he sailed a corvette from [[Honfleur]] to [[Le Havre]], ferrying king [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]].<ref name=guerin436 />\n\nHis uncle, [[Charles-Auguste Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville]], died in 1788 and bequeathed him his name; henceforth, Latouche added \"Tr\u00e9ville\" to his name, becoming the \"comte de Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville\".<ref name=guerin436 />\n\n[[File:Scanlatouchetreville.jpg|thumb|Letter by Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville]]\nAt the beginning of the [[French Revolution]] in 1789, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was elected deputy of the [[Estates General (France)|Nobility]]<ref name=levot296 /> for the [[bailiwick]] of [[Montargis]]; he went on to sit at the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]] and held this position until it adjourned on 10 October 1791.<ref name=guerin436 /> Latouche took a liberal posture and was among the first nobles to join forces with the Third Estate.<ref name=levot296 /> In September 1791, after king Louis XVI approved the new constitution, the National Constituent Assembly disbanded, and Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville resumed his naval activities.\n\n[[File:Rouget - Louis-Ren\u00e9-Madeleine Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville, contre-amiral en 1792 (1745-1804).jpg|left|upright|thumb|Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as a Rear-Admiral, in 1792. [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis-Philippe]] commissioned the painting for the History Museum of Versailles in 1835;[[Georges Rouget]] painted it in 1840.]]\n\nLatouche had held the rank of Rear-Admiral since 20 December 1790 reform of the navy.<ref name=guerin436 /> In this capacity, in 1792 he took command of a four-ship squadron in [[Brest, France|Brest]].<ref name=levot296 /> He sailed from Brest to [[Toulon]], on his flagship the [[French ship Languedoc (1766)|''Languedoc'']], to attach his division to the Mediterranean squadron under Rear-admiral [[Laurent Jean Fran\u00e7ois Truguet|Truguet]].<ref name=levot296 /> He took part in raids against [[Oneglia]], [[Cagliari]] and [[Nice]]<ref name=hennequin110 /> during the [[French Revolutionary Wars: Campaigns of 1796#Italy|Army of Italy]], and joined in the attack on [[Sardinia]] in October 1792 (which turned out to be a failure when the expeditionary corps was repulsed). Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville and Truguet then returned to Toulon.\n\n[[File:Moniteur-Latouche-Naples.png|thumb|upright|''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]'' relates Latouche's mission to Naples.]]\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville was promoted to Rear-Admiral on 1 January 1793.<ref name=levot296 /> He was then sent on a mission to [[Napoli]], after that kingdom's ambassador to [[Constantinople]] had precipitated a diplomatic conflict by insulting his French counterpart. Latouche threatened to bombard the city, and obtained apologies from [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies]].<ref name=granier235>Granier, p.235</ref> Latouche then departed, but had to double back to Napoli to repair due to gale-force winds, eventually making his rendezvous with Truguet on 8 February 1793.<ref name=granier235 /> On 14 February, they landed 6,000 volunteers at Cagliari, who had to reembark under fire and in a gale two days later.<ref name=granier235 /> The fleet then returned to Toulon once more.<ref name=granier235 />\n\nIn March 1793, amid the [[War of the First Coalition]], Latouche took command of the \"Naval Army of the Ocean\" (the Brest fleet), but as soon as he took up his position, revolutionary subordinates denounced him as an aristocrat. On 15 September,<ref name=guerin437>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.437</ref> at the height of the [[Reign of Terror]], he was arrested as a \"suspect\" on orders of the [[Committee of Public Safety]],<ref name=guerin437 /> and cashiered on 3 October.<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=\"guerin458\">Gu\u00e9rin, ''Histoire maritime de France'', p.458</ref> He spent one year in [[La Force Prison]],<ref name=guerin437 /> and was freed only on 20 September 1794,<ref name=guerin437 /> after the [[Thermidorian Reaction]].\n\nFreed, Latouche returned to Montargis, where he was appointed chief of the Legion of the [[National Guard (France)|National Guard]] for the district.<ref name=guerin437 /> A [[Freemasonry|Freemason]], he rose to ''V\u00e9n\u00e9rable'' in the Lodge ''Les Disciples d\u2019Heredom et de la Madeleine R\u00e9unis'', of Montargis.<ref>{{Cite book|first=Jean-Marc|last=Van Hille|title=Dictionnaire des marins francs-ma\u00e7ons, Gens de mer et professions connexes aux XVIIIe, XIXe et XXe si\u00e8cles|publisher=L'Harmattan|year=2011|page=305}}</ref> Latouche was rehabilitated under the [[French Directory|Directoire]] and had his rank reinstated in December 1795,<ref name=levot296 /> but nonetheless was left for five years without a command in the Navy.<ref name=levot296 /> From 1797 to 1798, he managed equipment for the Navy with a ship-owner friend, and by 1799 he had grown so desperate that he advertised in ''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]'' for privateer captainships.<ref>Granier, p.236</ref> It was not until 1799 that he returned to active duty.<ref name=guerin437 />\n\n=== Service at the Flottille de Boulogne ===\nIn 1799, Latouche was appointed to lead a naval division in Brest, with his mark on the 74-gun [[French ship Mont-Blanc (1791)|''Mont-Blanc'']].<ref name=guerin437 /> Soon after, he was appointed to command the full Brest fleet,<ref name=guerin437 /> and transferred his flag onto the 110-gun [[French ship Terrible (1779)|''Terrible'']].<ref name=guerin437 /> Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville defended the harbour until the government decided to disband the naval Army of Brest; Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville then sailed four of its ships to Rochefort.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n[[File:Boulogne.jpg|thumb|Nelson fails against the flotilla of Latouche Tr\u00e9ville near Boulogne, 15 August 1801]]\nSoon after, advised by Navy minister [[Pierre-Alexandre-Laurent Forfait|Forfait]],<ref name=levot296 /> [[French Consulate|First Consul]] [[Napoleon I of France|Bonaparte]] chose Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville to organise and lead the ''[[Flottille de Boulogne]]''. This vast fleet of small ships was ostensibly designed to ferry an invasion army to England,<ref name=levot296 /><ref name=guerin437 /> but was in fact a disinformation ploy to pressure the British into negotiating the [[Treaty of Amiens]].<ref>Farr\u00e8re, p.298</ref> The ploy helped to disguise the true goal of the French military, which was massing armies in Boulogne for an invasion of Austria.<ref>Granier, p.244</ref> Soon after his arrival, on 4 August and 15 August 1801, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville repelled the [[Raid on Boulogne (1801)|several British raids]] that Admiral [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson]] launched to destroy the ''Flottille''.<ref name=levot296 />\n\n=== Service at Saint-Domingue ===\nDuring the [[Peace of Amiens]], Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville was appointed to command the naval squadron of Rochefort,<ref name=hennequin111>Hennequin, p.111</ref> comprising six ships of the line, six frigates and two corvettes,<ref name=guerin437 />  in the fleet of Admiral [[Villaret de Joyeuse]],<ref name=levot296 /> ferrying 3,000 men of the Army of Rhine for the [[Saint-Domingue expedition]].<ref name=guerin437 /> Latouche fought his way into the harbour of [[Port-au-Prince]], captured its forts and landed the troops.<ref name=guerin437 /> He and General Boudet captured [[Port-au-Prince]] and [[L\u00e9og\u00e2ne]]. Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville managed to obtain the peaceful surrender of General Laplume, while, in the south, General [[Charles Leclerc (general, born 1772)|Leclerc]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} forced [[Toussaint L'Ouverture]] and Christophe to submit to French authority.<ref name=granier246>Granier, p.246</ref>\n\nWith [[Villaret de Joyeuse]]'s departure in April 1802, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville stayed in Saint-Domingue with four ships of the line, nine frigates and five corvettes.<ref name=granier246 /> After the restoration of slavery on 20 May 1802, a new rebellion broke out, which overwhelmed the yellow-fever-stricken army of General Leclerc. Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville defended the harbours in the south, appointing [[Jean-Baptiste Philibert Willaumez|Willaumez]] to the western naval station of Saint-Domingue.<ref name=granier246 /> The situation grew even more desperate after the British started the [[War of the Third Coalition]] in May 1803: Willaumez had to return to France to repair his frigate, damaged in the [[Action of 28 June 1803]], and the British effected a [[Blockade of Saint-Domingue]] that ended with the complete destruction of Rochambeau's army.<ref name=granier246 /> In October 1803, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville obtained free passage from the British due to his poor health, and returned to France.<ref name=hennequin111 /><ref name=granier246 />\n\n=== Service as commander of the fleet of Toulon ===\n\n[[File:Rouget - Louis-Ren\u00e9-Madeleine Levassor de La Touche-Tr\u00e9ville, vice-amiral en 1803 (1745-1804).jpg|right|upright|thumb|Portrait of Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville as a Vice-Admiral, in 1803. [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis-Philippe]] commissioned the painting for the History Museum of Versailles in 1835; [[Georges Rouget]] painted it in 1840.]]\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville was made a vice-Admiral in December 1803. Returned to France, he was appointed general inspector of the coasts of the Mediterranean, before taking command of the fleet of Toulon,<ref name=hennequin111 /> with his flag on the brand-new 80-gun ''[[French ship Bucentaure (1804)|Bucentaure]]''.<ref name=guerin438>Gu\u00e9rin, ''Les Marins illustres'', p.438</ref> At the time, the squadron counted only seven ships of the line and four frigates, and discipline was much weakened;<ref name=hennequin111 /> in particular, Navy officers slept aboard their ships only when forced to do so by their duty.<ref name=hennequin111 /> Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville made a point to live on his ship, and morale quickly improved under his example and leadership.<ref name=hennequin111 />\n\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville decided to have one ship or frigate patrol for three days outside the harbour, in rotation, while another would always be ready to put to sail at the first signal.<ref name=hennequin112>Hennequin, p.112</ref> Furthermore, the entire squadron regularly scrambled to support the cruisers whenever superior British forces ventured into Toulon harbour, preventing the British from conducting useful reconnaissance of French activities in the area.<ref name=hennequin112 /> Over the time, the squadron received three more ships of the line and three more frigates as reinforcements.<ref name=hennequin112 />\n\nIn late June 1804, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville suffered a relapse of a medical condition contracted at Saint-Domingue.<ref group=Note>Hennequin (''Biographie maritime'', vol.2, p.112), Levot (''Gloires maritimes de la France'', p.297), Gu\u00e9rin (''Marins illustres'', p.629) and Taillemite (''Dictionnaire des marins fran\u00e7ais'', p.310) are all vague as to what exact medical condition is involved. Hennequin is the most precise on this question, stating that \"around the last days of July, the symptoms of the disease that had required his return from Saint-Domingue to Europe became very obvious, and soon took an alarming turn.\" (\"''Vers les derniers jours du mois de juillet, les sympt\u00f4mes de la maladie qui avait n\u00e9cessit\u00e9 son retour de Saint-Domingue en Europe se d\u00e9clar\u00e8rent vivement, et bient\u00f4t elle prit un caract\u00e8re alarment.''\"). Levot states that Latouche \"succumbed on ''Bucentaure'' to the consequences of the disease he had contracted at Saint-Domingue\" (\"''Le 19 ao\u00fbt 1804, il succombait sur le ''Bucentaure'' aux suites de la maladie qu'il avait contract\u00e9e \u00e0 Saint-Domingue''\").</ref> However, he constantly refused to transfer ashore, stating \"An admiral is only too glad when he can die under the flag of his ship.\"<ref group=Note>\"Un amiral est trop heureux lorsqu'il peut mourir sous le pavillon de son vaisesau.\" Quote in Hennequin, p.112</ref><ref name=hennequin112 /> Indeed, after a 10-day struggle, on 19 August, Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville  died aboard ''Bucentaure''.<ref name=hennequin112 /> Lord Nelson later wrote:\n{{cquote|The French papers say he died of walking so often up to the signal-post to watch us: I always pronounced that would be his death.<ref>Bradford, last page of chapter 32.</ref>}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nLatouche-Tr\u00e9ville  was buried in Toulon graveyard. In 1810, a seven-metre-high pyramidal mausoleum was built at the S\u00e9maphore de la Croix des Signaux, at Cape C\u00e9pet, from where Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville had observed the British in his last year.<ref>Granier, p.248</ref> On 14 October 1902, military authorities decided to move the mausoleum<ref group=Note>Allegedly, because they saw the mausoleum as a potential [[daymark]] for an enemy fleet. Emmanuel Davin, ''Les amis du vieux Toulon''; quoted in Granier, p.249.</ref> to the military graveyard of [[Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer]]; the body was transferred on  29 April 1903.<ref>[http://www.ville-saintmandrier.fr/office/tourisme/cimetiere.html ville-saintmandrier.fr] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416135821/http://www.ville-saintmandrier.fr/office/tourisme/cimetiere.html |date=16 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFrench authors and historians often compared Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville to Nelson, partly because he fought and defeated him in the [[Raids on Boulogne]], partly because, had it not been for his untimely death, he would have opposed Nelson at [[Trafalgar Campaign|Trafalgar]].<ref>R\u00e9mi Monaque, ''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville, 1745\u20131804 : l'amiral qui d\u00e9fiait Nelson'', \u00e9ditions SPM, 2000, {{ISBN|2-901952-36-4}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Arc de Triomphe mg 6823.jpg|right|upright|thumb|LATOUCHE [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the [[Arc de Triomphe]] (left column, 10th from top).]]\nThe name ''Latouche'' was [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|inscribed]] on the north face of the [[Arc de Triomphe]] in his honour.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Notice historique sur l'Arc de Triomphe et l'\u00c9toile |last= Thierry |first=J. |author2=Coulon, G.  |year=1838 |publisher=Rosselin |location=Paris |language=French |page=24 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNxSAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA24 |accessdate=6 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThree ships of the [[French Navy]] have been named [[French ship Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in his honour: the steam aviso [[French aviso Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (1860)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in 1860; the armoured cruiser [[French cruiser Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] in 1892; and the [[Georges Leygues-class frigate|F70-type]] destroyer [[French frigate Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (D646)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']], presently in commission.\n{{Gallery\n|title=Ships of the French Navy named ''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville''\n|width=200\n|height=\n|lines=2\n|align=center\n|File:Le RenardWiki.jpg|The steam 2nd-class aviso ''Renard'', similar to [[French aviso Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']] (1860-1886)\n|File:Latouche-Treville far134.jpg|The armoured cruiser [[French cruiser Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']]\n|File:FS Latouche Treville (D 646).jpg|The [[Georges Leygues-class frigate|F70-type]] destroyer [[French frigate Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville (D646)|''Latouche-Tr\u00e9ville'']]\n}}\n\n== Notes, citations and references ==\n{{Portal|France|Biography|American Revolutionary War|United States|North America}}\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== References ===\n* {{cite book|title=Nelson: The Essential Hero|first=Ernle|last=Bradford|authorlink=Ernle Bradford|publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited|year=1977|isbn=0-333-18561-7}}\n* {{cite book|title=The A to Z of the Discovery and Exploration of Australia\n|first=Alan|last=Day|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0810868106}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la Marine fran\u00e7aise|first=Claude|last=Farr\u00e8re|authorlink=Claude Farr\u00e8re|publisher=Flammarion|year=1956|place=Paris|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Les marins illustres de la France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1845|publisher=Belin-Leprieur et Morizot|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uutuoMfBe4AC|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire maritime de France|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=L\u00e9on|authorlink=L\u00e9on Gu\u00e9rin|year=1857|publisher=Dufour et Mulat|url=https://books.google.com/?id=95BKAAAAMAAJ|language=French|volume=5}}\n* {{cite book|title=Biographie maritime ou notices historiques sur la vie et les campagnes des marins c\u00e9l\u00e8bres fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers|last=Hennequin|first=Joseph Fran\u00e7ois Gabriel|year=1835|publisher=Regnault \u00e9diteur|location=Paris|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YbdCAAAAYAAJ|language=French|volume=2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Les gloires maritimes de la France: notices biographiques sur les plus c\u00e9l\u00e8bres marins|last=Levot|first=Prosper|authorlink=Prosper Levot|year=1866|publisher=Bertrand|url=https://books.google.com/?id=08O_XGLO43QC|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Captain Cook, Master of the Seas|first=Frank M.|last=Lynn|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0300184310|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ridlr1YNgXwC}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=1}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=2}}\n* {{cite book|first=\u00c9tienne|last=Taillemite|year=2002|title=Dictionnaire des Marins fran\u00e7ais|isbn=2-84734-008-4|publisher=Tallandier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Latouche Treville}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1804 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Rochefort, Charente-Maritime]]\n[[Category:French Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:French naval commanders of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n[[Category:French Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe]]\n[[Category:People of the Haitian Revolution]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCapture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis-Ren%C3%A9_Levassor_de_Latouche_Tr%C3%A9ville"}
{"title_page": "A Life in the Theatre", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = A Life in the Theatre\n| image      = alifeinthetheatre.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption    = Poster for the 2010 Broadway Revival\n| writer     = [[David Mamet]]\n| characters = Robert (stage veteran) John (young actor)\n| premiere   = 1977\n| place      = [[Theatre De Lys]]\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    = \n| genre      = Comedy\n| web        = http://broadwaysbestshows.com/show/A-Life-in-the-Theatre\n}}\n\n'''''A Life in the Theatre''''' is a 1977 play by [[David Mamet]].\n\nIt focuses on the relationship between two actors, the play's only characters. One, Robert, is a stage veteran while John is a young, promising actor. As the play goes on they are involved in a variety of productions, and gradually their relationship begins to change.\n\n==Production history==\nIt was first produced in the US at the [[Goodman Theatre]], Chicago, [[Illinois]], in February 1977, with [[Mike Nussbaum]] and [[Joe Mantegna]] and directed by [[Gregory Mosher]].<ref>[http://www.theatrewesternsprings.com/Actives/archives/LifeTheatre/LifeInTheTheatre.htm \"A Life in the Theatre\" production note, history\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821050012/http://www.theatrewesternsprings.com/Actives/archives/LifeTheatre/LifeInTheTheatre.htm |date=August 21, 2008 }}, theatrewesternsprings.com, accessed February 22, 2009</ref>  It was revived at the Goodman in March 2006, directed by Artistic Director [[Robert Falls]].<ref>[http://www.goodmantheatre.org/News/PressRoom/Imagery/LifeInTheTheatre/ \"Images of production\"] goodmantheatre.org, accessed February 22, 2009  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123095853/http://www.goodmantheatre.org/News/PressRoom/Imagery/LifeInTheTheatre/ |date=November 23, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.goodmantheatre.org/Season/0506/A-Life-in-the-Theatre/ \"'A Life in the Theatre' 2006\"] goodmantheatre.org, accessed October 25, 2015</ref>\n\nThe play premiered [[Off-Broadway]] at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]] (then the Theatre De Lys) in October 1977 through July 1978, with [[Ellis Rabb]] as Robert and [[Peter Evans (actor)|Peter Evans]] as John and directed by [[Gerald Gutierrez]].<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=661 Off-Broadway listing, 1977 production] lortel.org, accessed February 22, 2009.</ref> It was again produced Off-Broadway at the Jewish Repertory Theatre in February 1992 through March 1992, with [[F. Murray Abraham]] as Robert and [[Anthony Fusco]] as John.<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=1481 Off-Broadway Database listing, 1992 production] lortel.org, accessed February 22, 2009</ref>\n\nIt was the featured play at UCSC's [[Shakespeare Santa Cruz]] summer festival in 1986, with [[Trevor Baxter]] and [[Paul Whitworth]].\n\nNotable UK productions include a run at London's [[Apollo Theatre]], from February 2 to April 30, 2005 with [[Patrick Stewart]] as Robert and [[Joshua Jackson]] playing John,<ref>Loveridge, Lizzie. [http://www.curtainup.com/lifeinthetheatrelond.html \"Review:A Life In the Theatre\"], curtainup.com, February 3, 2005</ref> and an [[Edinburgh Fringe]] production in 2008 by [[Schadenfreude Productions]], with David Cann as Robert and [[Jonathan Rhodes]] as John.\n\nAnother revival featuring [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[T. R. Knight|T.R. Knight]] and directed by [[Neil Pepe]] began performances on Broadway in a limited engagement, opened officially on October 12, 2010 for a 15-week run, through January 2, 2011.<ref>Hetrick, Adam and Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141101-Mamets-A-Life-in-the-Theatre-Sets-Broadway-Opening-and-Closing-Dates  \"Mamet's 'A Life in the Theatre' Sets Broadway Opening and Closing Dates\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817094531/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141101-Mamets-A-Life-in-the-Theatre-Sets-Broadway-Opening-and-Closing-Dates |date=August 17, 2010 }} playbill.com, July 12, 2010</ref> However, after mixed critical reviews and low box office returns, the show closed on November 28, 2010 after 24 previews and 56 regular performances.<ref>Gans, Andrew and Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/david-mamets-a-life-in-the-theatre-closes-on-broadway-nov.-28-173872# \"David Mamet's 'A Life in the Theatre' Closes on Broadway Nov. 28\"] Playbill, November 28, 2010</ref>\n\nOpened for a three-week run on January 31, 2019 at [[The Arctic Playhouse]].\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe play was first adapted into a 1979 television film ''[[A Life in the Theatre (1979 film)|A Life in the Theatre]]'', with Peter Evans and Ellis Rabb reprising their roles from the 1977 Off-Broadway production.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor|first=John J.|title=TV: Mamet's \u2018A Life in the Theater\u2019|date=3 October 1979|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/03/archives/tv-mamets-a-life-in-the-theater.html|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Leydon|first=Joe|title=Review: \u2018A Life in the Theatre\u2019|date=16 September 1993|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/1993/film/reviews/a-life-in-the-theatre-1200433345/|accessdate=15 August 2017|quote=At best, pic is a slight improvement over the play\u2019s previous TV adaptation, an unfortunately literal-minded videotaping (produced in the late 1970s for PBS) that\u2019s memorable only for recording the brilliant performances of Ellis Rabb and the late Peter Evans, stars of the original 1977 off-Broadway production.}}</ref>\n\nThe play was adapted into an [[A Life in the Theatre (1993 film)|another television movie in 1993]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/a_life_in_the_theatre/ |title=A Life in the Theatre (1993) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref> The teleplay was written by David Mamet. It was directed by [[Gregory Mosher]], and starred [[Matthew Broderick]] and [[Jack Lemmon]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IBDB title|488279}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110825104642/http://www.broadwaysbestshows.com/show/A-Life-in-the-Theatre A Life In The Theatre Official Website]\n\n{{Mamet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life in the Theatre}}\n[[Category:1977 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by David Mamet]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = A Life in the Theatre\n| image      = alifeinthetheatre.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption    = Poster for the 2010 Broadway Revival\n| writer     = [[David Mamet]]\n| characters = Robert (stage veteran) John (young actor)\n| premiere   = 1977\n| place      = [[Theatre De Lys]]\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    = \n| genre      = Comedy\n| web        = http://broadwaysbestshows.com/show/A-Life-in-the-Theatre\n}}\n\n'''''A Life in the Theatre''''' is a 1977 play by [[David Mamet]].\n\nIt focuses on the relationship between two actors, the play's only characters. One, Robert, is a stage veteran while John is a young, promising actor. As the play goes on they are involved in a variety of productions, and gradually their relationship begins to change.\n\n==Production history==\nIt was first produced in the US at the [[Goodman Theatre]], Chicago, [[Illinois]], in February 1977, with [[Mike Nussbaum]] and [[Joe Mantegna]] and directed by [[Gregory Mosher]].<ref>[http://www.theatrewesternsprings.com/Actives/archives/LifeTheatre/LifeInTheTheatre.htm \"A Life in the Theatre\" production note, history\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821050012/http://www.theatrewesternsprings.com/Actives/archives/LifeTheatre/LifeInTheTheatre.htm |date=August 21, 2008 }}, theatrewesternsprings.com, accessed February 22, 2009</ref>  It was revived at the Goodman in March 2006, directed by Artistic Director [[Robert Falls]].<ref>[http://www.goodmantheatre.org/News/PressRoom/Imagery/LifeInTheTheatre/ \"Images of production\"] goodmantheatre.org, accessed February 22, 2009  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123095853/http://www.goodmantheatre.org/News/PressRoom/Imagery/LifeInTheTheatre/ |date=November 23, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.goodmantheatre.org/Season/0506/A-Life-in-the-Theatre/ \"'A Life in the Theatre' 2006\"] goodmantheatre.org, accessed October 25, 2015</ref>\n\nThe play premiered [[Off-Broadway]] at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]] (then the Theatre De Lys) in October 1977 through July 1978, with [[Ellis Rabb]] as Robert and [[Peter Evans (actor)|Peter Evans]] as John and directed by [[Gerald Gutierrez]].<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=661 Off-Broadway listing, 1977 production] lortel.org, accessed February 22, 2009.</ref> It was again produced Off-Broadway at the Jewish Repertory Theatre in February 1992 through March 1992, with [[F. Murray Abraham]] as Robert and [[Anthony Fusco]] as John.<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=1481 Off-Broadway Database listing, 1992 production] lortel.org, accessed February 22, 2009</ref>\n\nIt was the featured play at UCSC's [[Shakespeare Santa Cruz]] summer festival in 1986, with [[Trevor Baxter]] and [[Paul Whitworth]].\n\nNotable UK productions include a run at London's [[Apollo Theatre]], from February 2 to April 30, 2005 with [[Patrick Stewart]] as Robert and [[Joshua Jackson]] playing John,<ref>Loveridge, Lizzie. [http://www.curtainup.com/lifeinthetheatrelond.html \"Review:A Life In the Theatre\"], curtainup.com, February 3, 2005</ref> and an [[Edinburgh Fringe]] production in 2008 by [[Schadenfreude Productions]], with David Cann as Robert and [[Jonathan Rhodes]] as John.\n\nAnother revival featuring [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[T.R. Knight]] and directed by [[Neil Pepe]] began performances on Broadway in a limited engagement, opened officially on October 12, 2010 for a 15-week run, through January 2, 2011.<ref>Hetrick, Adam and Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141101-Mamets-A-Life-in-the-Theatre-Sets-Broadway-Opening-and-Closing-Dates  \"Mamet's 'A Life in the Theatre' Sets Broadway Opening and Closing Dates\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817094531/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141101-Mamets-A-Life-in-the-Theatre-Sets-Broadway-Opening-and-Closing-Dates |date=August 17, 2010 }} playbill.com, July 12, 2010</ref> However, after mixed critical reviews and low box office returns, the show closed on November 28, 2010 after 24 previews and 56 regular performances.<ref>Gans, Andrew and Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/david-mamets-a-life-in-the-theatre-closes-on-broadway-nov.-28-173872# \"David Mamet's 'A Life in the Theatre' Closes on Broadway Nov. 28\"] Playbill, November 28, 2010</ref>\n\nOpened for a three-week run on January 31, 2019 at [[The Arctic Playhouse]].\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe play was first adapted into a 1979 television film ''[[A Life in the Theatre (1979 film)|A Life in the Theatre]]'', with Peter Evans and Ellis Rabb reprising their roles from the 1977 Off-Broadway production.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor|first=John J.|title=TV: Mamet's \u2018A Life in the Theater\u2019|date=3 October 1979|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/03/archives/tv-mamets-a-life-in-the-theater.html|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Leydon|first=Joe|title=Review: \u2018A Life in the Theatre\u2019|date=16 September 1993|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/1993/film/reviews/a-life-in-the-theatre-1200433345/|accessdate=15 August 2017|quote=At best, pic is a slight improvement over the play\u2019s previous TV adaptation, an unfortunately literal-minded videotaping (produced in the late 1970s for PBS) that\u2019s memorable only for recording the brilliant performances of Ellis Rabb and the late Peter Evans, stars of the original 1977 off-Broadway production.}}</ref>\n\nThe play was adapted into an [[A Life in the Theatre (1993 film)|another television movie in 1993]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/a_life_in_the_theatre/ |title=A Life in the Theatre (1993) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref> The teleplay was written by David Mamet. It was directed by [[Gregory Mosher]], and starred [[Matthew Broderick]] and [[Jack Lemmon]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IBDB title|488279}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110825104642/http://www.broadwaysbestshows.com/show/A-Life-in-the-Theatre A Life In The Theatre Official Website]\n\n{{Mamet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life in the Theatre}}\n[[Category:1977 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by David Mamet]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Life_in_the_Theatre"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in South Korea}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea\n | map1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea (Density).svg\n | legend1 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 20 April): {{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201399}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 100\u2013499}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 500\u2013999}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed 1000\u20139999}}{{legend|#630606|Confirmed \u226510000}}\n| map2 = Coronavirus Outbreak in South Korea over Time.gif\n| legend2 = Coronavirus pandemic in South Korea over time (since January 20, 2020).<br /><div style=\"{{linear-gradient|left|#ffffff, #ff0000}}; border:solid 1px black; width:50px; height:0.5em; float:left; position:relative; top:0.4em;\">&nbsp;</div> &nbsp; Number of cases ([[logarithmic scale|logarithmically]]){{legend|#e7e8e6|Day not included in map}}{{legend|#989896|Day included in map}}{{legend|#444443|Last day included in map}}\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = [[Incheon International Airport]]\n| location = South Korea\n| arrival_date = 20 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases = 8,114\n| confirmed_cases = 10,674\n| suspected_cases = 11,981\n| deaths = 236\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|ncov.mohw.go.kr/en}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in South Korea was announced on 20 January 2020.<ref name=\"mk\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4 \ud55c\uad6d\uc778 \uccab\ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778 |url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |website=MK |publisher=\uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |accessdate=24 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124134926/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The number of confirmed cases increased on 19 February by 20, and on 20 February by 58<ref name=\"Getnews_58_Shincheonji\">{{cite web|url=http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|script-title=ko:31\ubc88 \ud658\uc790 \uc5f0\uad00 \uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0\uad50\ud68c \ub300\ub0a8\ubcd1\uc6d0\uc11c \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 58\uba85, 1\uba85 \uc0ac\ub9dd|date=20 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102733/http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> or 70,<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\">{{cite news | last1= Shin | first1= Hyonhee | last2= Cha | first2= Sangmi | title= 'Like a zombie apocalypse': Residents on edge as coronavirus cases surge in South Korea |trans-title = <!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 20 February 2020 |agency=[[Thomson Reuters]] | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea-cases/like-a-zombie-apocalypse-residents-on-edge-as-coronavirus-cases-surge-in-south-korea-idUSKBN20E04F |accessdate=20 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/D1K5i |archivedate= 20 February 2020 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> giving a total of 346 confirmed cases on 21 February 2020, according to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea]] ([[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]]), with the sudden jump mostly attributed to \"Patient 31\" who participated in a gathering at a [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus|Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony]] church in [[Daegu]].<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korea reports 161 new cases, bringing total to 763; 7th death reported |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=24 February 2020 |date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224060714/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAmidst the fears of further contamination, mass gatherings in the affected cities were cancelled and a few hundred soldiers in [[Daegu]] are in isolation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seoul city to ban rallies, Shincheonji church services to curb virus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221112436/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soldiers in Daegu areas banned from leaving bases, meeting visitors |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221145843/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 4 February 2020, in order to help prevent the spread of COVID-19, South Korea began denying entry to foreigners traveling from [[Hubei|Hubei Province]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | title=S. Korea Bars Foreigners Traveling from Hubei Province | access-date=2 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309151058/http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | archive-date=9 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-28/as-virus-spreads-koreans-blame-refusal-to-stop-chinese-visitors |title=As Virus Spreads, Koreans Blame Refusal to Stop Chinese Visitors |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2020-02-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nBy 9 April 2020, South Korea had about 10,423 cases and 204 deaths,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|title=Coronavirus South Korea|website=Worldometer|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173023/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with over 494,711 people having been tested, a [[case fatality rate]] of 1.95%, which is lower than the WHO's global case fatality rate of 4.34%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coronaboard.kr/en/|title=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|website=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324053131/https://coronaboard.kr/en/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSouth Korea introduced what was considered one of the largest and best-organised epidemic control programs in the world, along with Taiwan,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |title=Taiwan Has Been Shut Out of Global Health Discussions |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323222040/https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324085234/https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |title=Coronavirus Lessons from Singapore, Taiwan and Hong Kong |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324174105/https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Different measures have been taken to screen the mass population for the virus, and isolate any infected people as well as trace and quarantine those who contacted them, without further lockdown.<ref name=science20200317 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |title=Coronavirus in South Korea: How 'trace, test and treat' may be saving lives |first=Laura |last=Bicker |work=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190601/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rapid and extensive tests taken by South Korea have been judged successful in limiting the spread of the outbreak despite not using the drastic measure of quarantining entire cities.<ref name=science20200317>{{cite journal |journal=Science |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success? |first=Dennis |last=Normile |date=17 March 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abb7566 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205413/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |title=South Korea's coronavirus lessons: Quick, easy tests; monitoring |first=Kelly |last=Kasulis |date=19 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320144222/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |title=South Korea took rapid, intrusive measures against Covid-19 \u2013 and they worked |first1=Alexis |last1=Dudden |first2=Andrew |last2=Marks |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320143716/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 200\n | direction = vertical\n\n | image1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea.svg\n | caption1 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 20 April): {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}{{legend|#00cc00|14 days no confirmed cases}}\n\n| image2 = COVID-19 outbreak South Korea per capita cases map.svg\n| caption2 = Confirmed cases per million residents by province or city\n\n | image3 = Confirmed Cases of Coronavirus in South Korea (English version).png\n | caption3 = Number of confirmed coronavirus cases by provinces & special cities.\n}}\n\nDuring the first four weeks, South Korea controlled the potential spread of COVID-19 by using high-tech resources like tracking the use of credit cards and checking CCTV footage of confirmed patients. However, since 18 February, the number of cases increased to more than 1,700 after discovery of the fact that patient No. 31 was a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus]]. Some media reported that was difficult for [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] to screen the patient because Shincheonji teaches that illness is sin. Many members were uncooperative with KCDC and could not be contacted.<ref name=fp20200227>{{cite web | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | title=Cults and Conservatives Spread Coronavirus in South Korea | access-date=4 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307042428/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | archive-date=7 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Shincheonji denied this, and other sources report that the sect did cooperate with the authorities.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| title=Opinion &#124; Being Called a Cult is One Thing, Being Blamed for an Epidemic is Quite Another| newspaper=The New York Times| date=9 March 2020| last1=Rashid| first1=Raphael| access-date=21 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321153230/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| archive-date=21 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> About half of confirmed cases were linked to the Shincheonji Church as of 27 February; this was verified by health officials.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title=How religion is playing a role in the spread of coronavirus in Korea | access-date=12 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301081155/https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | archive-date=1 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> As of 10 March, the KCDC was able to contact and test most of the Shincheonji Church members, with the total number of tests nationally standing at around 200,000.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===20 January \u2013 17 February===\n[[File:Shincheonji Daegu Church 9 20200302.jpg|thumb|left|Shincheonji Daegu Church]]\n[[File:0222 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uc608\ubc29\uc218\uce59 \ud3ec\uc2a4\ud130 \uc601\ubb38.jpg|thumb|right|Recommendations for preventing COVID-19 released by KCDC under the [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Ministry of Health and Welfare]] of South Korea.]]\nOn 20 January, the first confirmed case was identified as a 35-year-old Chinese woman. The first South Korean national to be infected occurred three days later was a 55-year-old man who worked in Wuhan and returned for a checkup with flu symptoms. The two infection reports were publicly released on 24 January.<ref name=\"mk\"/>\n\nOn 26 January, a third case as a 54-year-old South Korean man. He had used a rental car and visited three restaurants, a hotel, a convenience store and met his family before admitting himself to hospital. All these places were disinfected.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 27 January, a fourth case was reported as a 55-year-old South Korean man who returned from Wuhan on 20 January. He first experienced flu symptoms on 21 January and suffered further complications four days later, eventually turning himself in. Both cases were tallied into formal records on 27 January.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uad6d \ub124\ubc88\uc9f8 '\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098' \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u202655\uc0b4 \ub0a8\uc131 |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |work=[[The Hankyoreh]] |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=27 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127101855/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |archive-date=27 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, an update on the first four patients indicated that the first three patients were showing weaker symptoms and recovering well while the fourth patient was getting treatment from [[pneumonia]]. Rumours circulated that the fourth patient had died which health authorities denied.<ref name=\"twelve\" />\n\nTwo more confirmed cases were reported on 30 January with the fifth patient being a 32-year-old South Korean man who returned from his work at Wuhan on 24 January. The sixth patient was the first case in South Korea who had never visited Wuhan. The 56-year-old man caught the virus when visiting a restaurant with the third patient.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 2\uba85 \ub298\uc5b4\u00b7\u00b7\u00b76\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790, \uad6d\ub0b4 \ucd5c\ucd08 '2\ucc28\uac10\uc5fc' |url=http://www.doctorstimes.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=209807 |website=\uc758\uc0ac\uc2e0\ubb38 |publisher=\uc774\ud55c\uc194 |accessdate=30 January 2020|date = 30 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, a seventh patient was reported as a 28-year-old South Korean man returning from [[Wuhan]] on 23 January. He developed symptoms on 26 January, and was admitted to the hospital on 28 January.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098' 7\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u2026\uc6b0\ud55c\uc11c \uc785\uad6d\ud55c 28\uc138 \ud55c\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011368450&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver News |publisher=\uc5f0\ud569\ub274\uc2a4 |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> On the same day, four more patients were admitted into the record as the eighth patient, 62-year-old South Korean woman, returned from Wuhan. The ninth patient caught the virus from the fifth patient through direct contact while the tenth and the eleventh patient were the wife and child who were infected while visiting the sixth patient.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4: 11\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778...\ud604\uc7ac\uae4c\uc9c0 \ud655\uc9c4 \uc0ac\ub840 \uc815\ub9ac |url=https://www.bbc.com/korean/news-51320986 |newspaper=BBC News \ucf54\ub9ac\uc544 |accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, a 49-year-old Chinese national working in [[Japan]] as a tour guide was confirmed as the twelfth patient. He caught the virus while visiting a Japanese patient in Japan and entered South Korea through [[Gimpo International Airport]] on 19 January.<ref name=\"twelve\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098'\uad6d\ub0b4 12\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790\u2026\uc77c\ubcf8\ud658\uc790 \uc811\ucd09 49\uc138 \uc911\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011370927&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver |publisher=Yonhap News Agency |accessdate=1 February 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The KCDC confirmed an additional three cases on 2 February, bringing the total to fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|title=S. Korea Reports 3 More Cases of Novel Coronavirus, Total Now at 15|first=|date=2 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202014910/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|archive-date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA woman, who had returned from [[Thailand]] after a five-day vacation, was tested positive and confirmed as the sixteenth case on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korean woman travelling home from Thailand tests positive for virus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=4 February 2020 |date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204092646/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three more cases were confirmed on 5 February, bringing the total case count to 19. The seventeenth and nineteenth patients had attended a conference in Singapore and been in contact with an infected individual there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yna.kr/AEN20200205002356320|title=3 More Virus Cases Bring S. Korea's Total to 19, Two Confirmed after Trip to Singapore|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The very same day the KCDC announced that the second patient had been released from hospital after being tested negative in consecutive tests, becoming the country's first coronavirus patient to fully recover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|title=S. Korea Releases First Fully Recovered Coronavirus Patient from Hospital|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205133506/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ {{nowrap|Details of the first 30 confirmed cases in South Korea (As of 17 February 2020)}}\n! Case\n! Date\n! Age\n! Gender\n! Nationality\n! Place of stay\n! Hospital of admission\n! Visited Wuhan?\n! Entry date\n! Status\n! Contacts of case\n! Note\n! Source\n|-\n|1\n|20 January 2020\n|35\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|[[Incheon]]\n|Incheon Metropolitan City Medical Center, [[Incheon]]\n|Yes\n|19 January 2020\n|Discharged (6 February 2020)\n|45\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\">{{cite web |title=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d(COVID)-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669(\uc815\ub840\ube0c\ub9ac\ud551) |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea |date=12 February 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a20501000000&bid=0015 |access-date=28 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305155753/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a20501000000&bid=0015 |archive-date=5 March 2020 |